{"title_page": "Exotica (Bananarama album)", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Exotica\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Bananarama]]\n| cover      = Banana_exotica.JPG\n| alt        =\n| released   = 26 March 2001\n| recorded   = July 1999 - May 2000\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]], [[dance-pop]], [[Latin pop]]\n| length     =\n| label      = M6 Interactions\n| producer   = Pascal Caubet\n| prev_title = [[Master Series (Bananarama album)|Master Series]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[The Very Best of Bananarama]]\n| next_year  = 2001\n}}\n\n'''''Exotica''''' is the eighth [[studio album]] released by the British female vocal duo [[Bananarama]]. This is Bananarama's third album as a duo, and was produced by Pascal Caubet and issued only in [[France]] in 2001 on the M6 Interactions [[record label|label]]. The work is a combination of new compositions along with re-recordings of past Bananarama hits, including a [[Latin pop]] version of the U.S. and UK Top 10 hit, \"[[Cruel Summer (song)|Cruel Summer]]\".\n\nTwo promo-only singles were released from the album: \"If\" (which was abandoned mostly before release) and a [[cover version]] of [[George Michael]]'s \"[[Careless Whisper]]\". The album was not a commercial or critical success for Bananarama, but the few copies of \"If\" which made it to the French market have become one of the rarest items ever by the band, heavily sought after by fans and collectors.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n\n==Track listing==\n'''France CD version'''\n#\"If\" \u2014 3:52 <small>(P. Caubet, S. Dallin, K. Woodward)</small>\n#\"Starz\" \u2014 3:45 <small>(S. Dallin, T. Moran, Bassey Walker)</small>\n#\"What You Gonna Do\" \u2014 4:32 <small>(S. Dallin, B. Walker)</small>\n#\"[[Cruel Summer (song)|Cruel Summer]]\" \u2014 4:05 <small>(S. Jolley, T. Swain, S. Dallin, S. Fahey, K. Woodward)</small>\n#\"Crazy\" \u2014 4:01 <small>(S. Dallin, P. Hampartzyoumyan, K. Woodward)</small>\n#\"Boom\" \u2014 3:15 <small>(S. Dallin, P. de Havilland, B. Walker)</small>\n#\"[[Robert De Niro's Waiting...]]\" \u2014 3:24 <small>(S. Jolley, T. Swain, S. Dallin, S. Fahey, K. Woodward)</small>\n#\"[[Careless Whisper]]\" \u2014 4:02 <small>([[George Michael]], [[Andrew Ridgeley]])</small>\n#\"Sleep\" \u2014 4:06 <small>(S. Dallin, P. Statham, B. Walker, K. Woodward)</small>\n#\"[[I Heard a Rumour]]\" \u2014 3:53 <small>(S. Dallin, S. Fahey, K. Woodward, M. Stock, M. Aitken, P.  Waterman)</small>\n#\"Got a Thing for You\" \u2014 3:41 <small>(P. Caubet, S. Dallin, B. Walker, K. Woodward)</small>\n#\"[[Venus (Shocking Blue song)|Venus]]\" \u2014 3:38 <small>([[Robbie van Leeuwen|R. V. Leeuwen]])</small>\n\n'''Unreleased songs and demos{{cn|date=September 2018}}'''\n#\"You and I\"\n#\"You Are Not Me\"\n#\"U R My Baby\" #:<small>Available on the Disco Brothers CD album ''Disco Brothers Present Stars of the '80s''.</small>\n#\"Your Love Tastes So Sweet\"\n#\"Breathe\"\n#\"Finally\"\n#\"Blue Sky\"\n#\"Middle of Nowhere\"\n#\"[[Waterloo (ABBA song)|Waterloo]]\" #:<small>Available on the CDs ''A Song for Eurotrash'' and ''ABBA: A Tribute, The 25th Anniversary Celebration''.</small>\n#\"I'm Waiting\"\n#\"I Like It\"\n\n==Personnel==\n'''Bananarama'''\n*[[Sara Dallin]] - Vocals\n*[[Keren Woodward]] - Vocals\n\n'''Produced by'''\n*Krysty Music Ltd.\n\n'''Vocal arrangements'''\n*[[Sara Dallin]] on most songs\n*[[Keren Woodward]] on most songs\n*Bassey Walker on most songs\n\n'''Recorded at'''\n*Krysty Music Studios, Paris\n*Pat Studio, Paris\n\n'''Voices recorded at'''\n*Matrix Studios, London\n*North London Studios\n*Studio du Palais des Congres, Paris\n*Big Onion Studios, London\n\n'''Guitars'''\n*Vasken Sayrin on \"If\", \"Boom\", \"[[Careless Whisper]]\" and \"Got a Thing for You\"\n*Alejandro Otero on \"[[Cruel Summer (song)|Cruel Summer]]\"\n*Juan-Carlos Pellegrino on \"[[Careless Whisper]]\", \"Sleep\" and \"[[Venus (Shocking Blue song)|Venus]]\"\n\n'''Keyboards'''\n*Pascal Caubet on most songs\n*Juan Carlos Pellegrino on \"[[Cruel Summer (song)|Cruel Summer]]\"\n*Florent Enfer on \"[[Robert De Niro's Waiting...]]\", and \"[[I Heard a Rumour]]\"\n*Patrick Hampartzoumian on \"Crazy\"\n\n'''Programming'''\n*Florent Enfer on most songs\n*Patrick Hampartzoumian on \"Crazy\"\n\n'''Arrangements'''\n*Pascal Caubet and Florent Enfer on most songs\n*Bassey Walker and Peter de Havilland on \"What You Gonna Do\"\n*Patrick Hampartzoumian on \"Crazy\"\n\n'''Executive producer'''\n*Pascal Caubet\n\n'''Sound engineer'''\n*Juan Carlos Pellegrino\n\n'''Mixed by'''\n*Juan Carlos Pellegrino and Pascal Caubet on most songs\n*Patrick Hampartzoumian on \"Crazy\"\n\n{{Bananarama}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Exotica (Bananarama Album)}}\n[[Category:Bananarama albums]]\n[[Category:2001 albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Exotica\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Bananarama]]\n| cover      = Banana_exotica.JPG\n| alt        =\n| released   = March 2001\n| recorded   = July 1999 - May 2000\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]], [[dance-pop]], [[Latin pop]]\n| length     =\n| label      = M6 Interactions\n| producer   = Pascal Caubet\n| prev_title = [[Master Series (Bananarama album)|Master Series]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[The Very Best of Bananarama]]\n| next_year  = 2001\n}}\n\n'''''Exotica''''' is the eighth [[studio album]] released by the British female vocal duo [[Bananarama]]. This is Bananarama's third album as a duo, and was produced by Pascal Caubet and issued only in [[France]] in 2001 on the M6 Interactions [[record label|label]]. The work is a combination of new compositions along with re-recordings of past Bananarama hits, including a [[Latin pop]] version of the U.S. and UK Top 10 hit, \"[[Cruel Summer (song)|Cruel Summer]]\".\n\nTwo promo-only singles were released from the album: \"If\" (which was abandoned mostly before release) and a [[cover version]] of [[George Michael]]'s \"[[Careless Whisper]]\". The album was not a commercial or critical success for Bananarama, but the few copies of \"If\" which made it to the French market have become one of the rarest items ever by the band, heavily sought after by fans and collectors.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n\n==Track listing==\n'''France CD version'''\n#\"If\" \u2014 3:52 <small>(P. Caubet, S. Dallin, K. Woodward)</small>\n#\"Starz\" \u2014 3:45 <small>(S. Dallin, T. Moran, Bassey Walker)</small>\n#\"What You Gonna Do\" \u2014 4:32 <small>(S. Dallin, B. Walker)</small>\n#\"[[Cruel Summer (song)|Cruel Summer]]\" \u2014 4:05 <small>(S. Jolley, T. Swain, S. Dallin, S. Fahey, K. Woodward)</small>\n#\"Crazy\" \u2014 4:01 <small>(S. Dallin, P. Hampartzyoumyan, K. Woodward)</small>\n#\"Boom\" \u2014 3:15 <small>(S. Dallin, P. de Havilland, B. Walker)</small>\n#\"[[Robert De Niro's Waiting...]]\" \u2014 3:24 <small>(S. Jolley, T. Swain, S. Dallin, S. Fahey, K. Woodward)</small>\n#\"[[Careless Whisper]]\" \u2014 4:02 <small>([[George Michael]], [[Andrew Ridgeley]])</small>\n#\"Sleep\" \u2014 4:06 <small>(S. Dallin, P. Statham, B. Walker, K. Woodward)</small>\n#\"[[I Heard a Rumour]]\" \u2014 3:53 <small>(S. Dallin, S. Fahey, K. Woodward, M. Stock, M. Aitken, P.  Waterman)</small>\n#\"Got a Thing for You\" \u2014 3:41 <small>(P. Caubet, S. Dallin, B. Walker, K. Woodward)</small>\n#\"[[Venus (Shocking Blue song)|Venus]]\" \u2014 3:38 <small>([[Robbie van Leeuwen|R. V. Leeuwen]])</small>\n\n'''Unreleased songs and demos{{cn|date=September 2018}}'''\n#\"You and I\"\n#\"You Are Not Me\"\n#\"U R My Baby\" #:<small>Available on the Disco Brothers CD album ''Disco Brothers Present Stars of the '80s''.</small>\n#\"Your Love Tastes So Sweet\"\n#\"Breathe\"\n#\"Finally\"\n#\"Blue Sky\"\n#\"Middle of Nowhere\"\n#\"[[Waterloo (ABBA song)|Waterloo]]\" #:<small>Available on the CDs ''A Song for Eurotrash'' and ''ABBA: A Tribute, The 25th Anniversary Celebration''.</small>\n#\"I'm Waiting\"\n#\"I Like It\"\n\n==Personnel==\n'''Bananarama'''\n*[[Sara Dallin]] - Vocals\n*[[Keren Woodward]] - Vocals\n\n'''Produced by'''\n*Krysty Music Ltd.\n\n'''Vocal arrangements'''\n*[[Sara Dallin]] on most songs\n*[[Keren Woodward]] on most songs\n*Bassey Walker on most songs\n\n'''Recorded at'''\n*Krysty Music Studios, Paris\n*Pat Studio, Paris\n\n'''Voices recorded at'''\n*Matrix Studios, London\n*North London Studios\n*Studio du Palais des Congres, Paris\n*Big Onion Studios, London\n\n'''Guitars'''\n*Vasken Sayrin on \"If\", \"Boom\", \"[[Careless Whisper]]\" and \"Got a Thing for You\"\n*Alejandro Otero on \"[[Cruel Summer (song)|Cruel Summer]]\"\n*Juan-Carlos Pellegrino on \"[[Careless Whisper]]\", \"Sleep\" and \"[[Venus (Shocking Blue song)|Venus]]\"\n\n'''Keyboards'''\n*Pascal Caubet on most songs\n*Juan Carlos Pellegrino on \"[[Cruel Summer (song)|Cruel Summer]]\"\n*Florent Enfer on \"[[Robert De Niro's Waiting...]]\", and \"[[I Heard a Rumour]]\"\n*Patrick Hampartzoumian on \"Crazy\"\n\n'''Programming'''\n*Florent Enfer on most songs\n*Patrick Hampartzoumian on \"Crazy\"\n\n'''Arrangements'''\n*Pascal Caubet and Florent Enfer on most songs\n*Bassey Walker and Peter de Havilland on \"What You Gonna Do\"\n*Patrick Hampartzoumian on \"Crazy\"\n\n'''Executive producer'''\n*Pascal Caubet\n\n'''Sound engineer'''\n*Juan Carlos Pellegrino\n\n'''Mixed by'''\n*Juan Carlos Pellegrino and Pascal Caubet on most songs\n*Patrick Hampartzoumian on \"Crazy\"\n\n{{Bananarama}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Exotica (Bananarama Album)}}\n[[Category:Bananarama albums]]\n[[Category:2001 albums]]\n", "name_user": "Bananarama official", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exotica_(Bananarama_album)"}
{"title_page": "Diocese of Kurunegala", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2017}}\n{{no footnotes|date=December 2017}}\nThe '''Diocese of Kurunegala''' is a [[diocese]] of the [[Church of Ceylon]] (which is part of the [[Anglican Communion]]). The See was erected in 1950 from that of [[Diocese of Colombo]], as one of two dioceses of the [[Church of England]] in [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]]. In September 2017 Keerthisiri Fernando, the Archdeacon of Nuwara Eliya of the Diocese of Colombo, was elected as the new Bishop of Kurunegala.\n\n== List of bishops==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:95%;\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color: #7F1734; color: white;\" | Bishops of Kurunegala\n\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: #D4B1BB; width: 5%;\" | From\n! style=\"background-color: #D4B1BB; width: 5%;\" | Until\n! style=\"background-color: #D4B1BB; width: 16%;\" | Incumbent\n! style=\"background-color: #D4B1BB; width: 20%;\" | Notes\n\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1950\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1962\n|'''[[Lakdasa De Mel]]'''\n|first Bishop of Kurunegala, installed on 2 February 1950; installed in May 1962 as [[Metropolitan Bishop]] of India, Pakistan, Burma and Ceylon\n\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1962\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1983\n|'''[[Lakshman Wickremasinghe]]'''\n|one of the youngest [[bishop]]s in the [[Anglican Communion]]\n\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1983\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 2000\n|'''[[Andrew Kumarage]]''' \n|\n\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 2000\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 2010\n|'''[[Kumara Illangasinghe]]''' \n|\n\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 2010\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 2015\n|'''[[Shantha Francis]]''' \n|first [[Tamil people|Tamil]] bishop, resigned in January 2015\n\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 2015\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 2017\n| colspan=3 | vacant\n\n|