{"title_page": "Tonderai Kasu", "text_new": "'''Tonderai Kasu''' is a community leader in [[Chitungwiza]], [[Zimbabwe]].<ref>https://allafrica.com/stories/202002130351.html</ref>. A medical doctor by training, he is currently the Acting Town Clerk or Acting Chief Executive, of the Chitungwiza Town Council<ref>https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/africa/2020-03-22-zimbabwe-system-inadequate-to-take-on-coronavirus/</ref><ref>http://www.rfi.fr/en/wires/20200322-zimbabwe-system-inadequate-take-coronavirus</ref><ref>https://sokwanele.com/2020/03/22/zimbabwe-health-system-inadequate-to-take-on-coronavirus-nehanda-radio/</ref><ref>https://akahinews.org/zimbabwe-system-inadequate-to-take-on-coronavirus/</ref><ref>https://health.grid.id/amp/352073486/index_user.html?page=all</ref><ref>https://www.pulselive.co.ke/news/world/zimbabwe-system-inadequate-to-take-on-coronavirus/gqxtj8p</ref>. He was appointed to the position of Acting Town Clerk by a resolution of the full council of the Municipality at its ordinary meeting held on the 10th of December 2019<ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/town-clerk-housing-director-suspended/</ref>. He has served as the Director of Health and Environmental Services of the Municipality in Chitungwiza, since April of 2016<ref>https://www.newsday.co.zw/2018/05/chitown-opens-up-on-cholera/</ref><ref>https://www.voazimbabwe.com/a/zimbabwe-doctors-doctors/5203707.html</ref>. He is also a member of the Environmental Management Committee for the [[Harare Metropolitan Province]]<ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/plans-for-chitungwiza-infectious-disease-hospital-gather-pace/</ref>. He is the former head of the accident and emergency department for St. Anne's Hospital<ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/parirenyatwa-hails-citimed-hospital/</ref>. As a leader in the health sector, he has managed facilities that have won awards for high quality of clinical care<ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-clinics-bag-four-awards/</ref>. In the country's third largest urban center, he has led the response to two cholera outbreaks<ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-cholera-outbreak-under-control/</ref><ref>https://www.newsday.co.zw/2018/05/chitown-opens-up-on-cholera/</ref><ref>https://bustop.tv/typhoid-scare-grips-chitungwiza/</ref><ref>https://www.openparly.co.zw/chitungwiza-blames-harare-for-cholera/</ref><ref>https://businesstimes.co.zw/cimas-assists-chitungwiza-cholera-centre/</ref><ref>https://www.voandebele.com/a/icholera-isibulele-abangamatshumi-amabili-lanye-eharare/4568785.html</ref>. As a senior public official having a background as a professional and as an administrator, and not as a politician, he has often encountered and experienced problems and setbacks in managing and meeting the expectations of the Chitungiwiza community's multiple stakeholders, given the politically polarized environment in Chitungwiza<ref>https://zimmorningpost.com/chitungwiza-employees-manhandled/</ref><ref>https://www.newzimbabwe.com/zanu-pf-activists-accused-of-waging-terror-on-chitungwiza-council-employees/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/municipal-director-hired-illegally/</ref>. Although having been criticized as a harsh enforcer of government policies, particularly with respect to illegal and informal trading in Chitungiwza, he has been at the forefront of spearheading urban renewal and development in Chitungwiza<ref>https://news.pindula.co.zw/2019/01/28/we-are-just-acting-on-a-govt-directive-councils-speak-on-demolition-of-illegal-tuckshops/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/harare-chitown-spearhead-urban-renewal-drive/</ref><ref>https://www.zimetro.co.zw/harare-city-council-says-demolitions-are-a-govt-directive/</ref><ref>https://www.dandaro.co.zw/we-are-just-acting-on-a-govt-directive-councils-speak-on-demolition-of-illegal-tuckshops/</ref><ref>https://zimmorningpost.com/chitungwiza-municipality-reads-riot-act-to-land-barons/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/allocate-vendors-operating-space/</ref><ref>https://nehandaradio.com/2019/03/05/chitungwiza-to-buy-150-skip-bins/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-clinics-to-get-pharmacies/</ref><ref>https://www.pressreader.com/zimbabwe/the-herald-zimbabwe/20171013/281599535723836</ref><ref>https://www.voazimbabwe.com/a/zimbabwe-cuba-doctors/5203717.html</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-to-recruit-17-nurses/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chi-town-interviews-aspiring-nurses/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-hosp-drugs-warehouses-near-completion/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/govt-rescues-chitungwiza/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/just-in-cuban-doctors-for-chitungwiza/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-gets-4-cuban-doctors/</ref><ref>https://adncuba.com/noticias-de-cuba/zimbabwe-contrataria-medicos-cubanos-para-detener-crisis-en-el-sector</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/passport-office-for-chitungwiza/</ref><ref>https://www.zimeye.net/2020/02/10/passport-application-issuance-to-be-decentralised-to-chitungwiza/</ref><ref>https://dailynews.co.zw/zengeza-to-house-passport-offices/</ref><ref>https://inzimnews.com/index.php/2020/02/13/passport-office-to-be-opened-in-chitungwiza/</ref><ref>https://mbaretimes.com/2019/12/12/govt-deploys-cuban-d/</ref><ref>https://zimbabwevoice.com/2019/12/13/govt-deploys-cuban-doctors-at-chitungwiza-hospital/</ref><ref>https://newsbeezer.com/zimbabwe/harare-chitown-spearhead-urban-renewal-drive/</ref><ref>https://vaaju.com/southafrica/harare-chitown-spearhead-urban-renewal-drive/</ref>. He has been active in sports development and in philanthropic work in the Chitungiwza community<ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-launches-mayors-cheer-fund/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-to-assist-600-families/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Zimbabwean politicians]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kasu, Tonderai}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "Tonderai Kasu is a community leader in [[Chitungwiza]], [[Zimbabwe]].<ref>https://allafrica.com/stories/202002130351.html</ref>. A medical doctor by training, he is currently the Acting Town Clerk or Acting Chief Executive, of the Chitungwiza Town Council<ref>https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/africa/2020-03-22-zimbabwe-system-inadequate-to-take-on-coronavirus/</ref><ref>http://www.rfi.fr/en/wires/20200322-zimbabwe-system-inadequate-take-coronavirus</ref><ref>https://sokwanele.com/2020/03/22/zimbabwe-health-system-inadequate-to-take-on-coronavirus-nehanda-radio/</ref><ref>https://akahinews.org/zimbabwe-system-inadequate-to-take-on-coronavirus/</ref><ref>https://health.grid.id/amp/352073486/index_user.html?page=all</ref><ref>https://www.pulselive.co.ke/news/world/zimbabwe-system-inadequate-to-take-on-coronavirus/gqxtj8p</ref>. He was appointed to the position of Acting Town Clerk by a resolution of the full council of the Municipality at its ordinary meeting held on the 10th of December 2019<ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/town-clerk-housing-director-suspended/</ref>. He has served as the Director of Health and Environmental Services of the Municipality in Chitungwiza, since April of 2016<ref>https://www.newsday.co.zw/2018/05/chitown-opens-up-on-cholera/</ref><ref>https://www.voazimbabwe.com/a/zimbabwe-doctors-doctors/5203707.html</ref>. He is also a member of the Environmental Management Committee for the [[Harare Metropolitan Province]]<ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/plans-for-chitungwiza-infectious-disease-hospital-gather-pace/</ref>. He is the former head of the accident and emergency department for St. Anne's Hospital<ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/parirenyatwa-hails-citimed-hospital/</ref>. As a leader in the health sector, he has managed facilities that have won awards for high quality of clinical care<ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-clinics-bag-four-awards/</ref>. In the country's third largest urban center, he has led the response to two cholera outbreaks<ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-cholera-outbreak-under-control/</ref><ref>https://www.newsday.co.zw/2018/05/chitown-opens-up-on-cholera/</ref><ref>https://bustop.tv/typhoid-scare-grips-chitungwiza/</ref><ref>https://www.openparly.co.zw/chitungwiza-blames-harare-for-cholera/</ref><ref>https://businesstimes.co.zw/cimas-assists-chitungwiza-cholera-centre/</ref><ref>https://www.voandebele.com/a/icholera-isibulele-abangamatshumi-amabili-lanye-eharare/4568785.html</ref>. As a senior public official having a background as a professional and as an administrator, and not as a politician, he has often encountered and experienced problems and setbacks in managing and meeting the expectations of the Chitungiwiza community's multiple stakeholders, given the politically polarized environment in Chitungwiza<ref>https://zimmorningpost.com/chitungwiza-employees-manhandled/</ref><ref>https://www.newzimbabwe.com/zanu-pf-activists-accused-of-waging-terror-on-chitungwiza-council-employees/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/municipal-director-hired-illegally/</ref>. Although having been criticized as a harsh enforcer of government policies, particularly with respect to illegal and informal trading in Chitungiwza, he has been at the forefront of spearheading urban renewal and development in Chitungwiza<ref>https://news.pindula.co.zw/2019/01/28/we-are-just-acting-on-a-govt-directive-councils-speak-on-demolition-of-illegal-tuckshops/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/harare-chitown-spearhead-urban-renewal-drive/</ref><ref>https://www.zimetro.co.zw/harare-city-council-says-demolitions-are-a-govt-directive/</ref><ref>https://www.dandaro.co.zw/we-are-just-acting-on-a-govt-directive-councils-speak-on-demolition-of-illegal-tuckshops/</ref><ref>https://zimmorningpost.com/chitungwiza-municipality-reads-riot-act-to-land-barons/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/allocate-vendors-operating-space/</ref><ref>https://nehandaradio.com/2019/03/05/chitungwiza-to-buy-150-skip-bins/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-clinics-to-get-pharmacies/</ref><ref>https://www.pressreader.com/zimbabwe/the-herald-zimbabwe/20171013/281599535723836</ref><ref>https://www.voazimbabwe.com/a/zimbabwe-cuba-doctors/5203717.html</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-to-recruit-17-nurses/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chi-town-interviews-aspiring-nurses/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-hosp-drugs-warehouses-near-completion/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/govt-rescues-chitungwiza/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/just-in-cuban-doctors-for-chitungwiza/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-gets-4-cuban-doctors/</ref><ref>https://adncuba.com/noticias-de-cuba/zimbabwe-contrataria-medicos-cubanos-para-detener-crisis-en-el-sector</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/passport-office-for-chitungwiza/</ref><ref>https://www.zimeye.net/2020/02/10/passport-application-issuance-to-be-decentralised-to-chitungwiza/</ref><ref>https://dailynews.co.zw/zengeza-to-house-passport-offices/</ref><ref>https://inzimnews.com/index.php/2020/02/13/passport-office-to-be-opened-in-chitungwiza/</ref><ref>https://mbaretimes.com/2019/12/12/govt-deploys-cuban-d/</ref><ref>https://zimbabwevoice.com/2019/12/13/govt-deploys-cuban-doctors-at-chitungwiza-hospital/</ref><ref>https://newsbeezer.com/zimbabwe/harare-chitown-spearhead-urban-renewal-drive/</ref><ref>https://vaaju.com/southafrica/harare-chitown-spearhead-urban-renewal-drive/</ref>. He has been active in sports development and in philanthropic work in the Chitungiwza community<ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-launches-mayors-cheer-fund/</ref><ref>https://www.herald.co.zw/chitungwiza-to-assist-600-families/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Zimbabwean politicians]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kasu, Tonderai}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Bensci54", "label": "safe", "comment": "bold subject", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tonderai_Kasu"}
{"title_page": "Ziyad ibn Abihi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name            = Ziyad ibn Abihi\n| image           = Arab-Sasanian Dirham in the name of Ziyad ibn Abi Sufyan.jpg\n| image_size      = 250\n| alt             = \n| caption         = Silver ''[[dirham]]'' following [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]] motives, struck in the name of \"Ziyad ibn Abi Sufyan\"\n| birth_date      = 622\n| birth_place     = \n| death_date      = 673\n| death_place     = \n| monarch1        = [[Mu'awiya I]]\n| office1         = [[List of Umayyad Governors of Iraq|Umayyad governor of Basra]]\n| term1           = June/July 665\u2013670\n| predecessor1    = Al-Harith ibn Abd Allah al-Azdi{{efn|Al-Harith ibn Abd Allah al-Azdi served four months as governor of Basra and had been appointed effectively as a placeholder in between the dismissal of [[Abd Allah ibn Amir]] and the appointment of Ziyad.{{sfn|Morony|1987|page=76}}}}\n| successor1      = \n| monarch2        = Mu'awiya I\n| office2         = [[List of Umayyad Governors of Iraq|Umayyad governor of Iraq]]\n| term2           = 670\u2013673\n| predecessor2    = ''Post established'' \n| successor2      = [[Abdallah ibn Khalid ibn Asid]] (in Kufa) <br /> Samura ibn Jundab al-Fazari (in Basra)\n| parents         = Sumayya & [[Abu Sufyan]] (illegitimate)\n| spouse          = {{plainlist|\n*Mu'adha bint Sakhr al-Uqayliyya \n*Marjana \n*Bint Muhajir ibn Hakim ibn Taliq \n*Bint Qa'qa ibn Ma'bad ibn Zurara al-Darimiyya \n*Lubaba bint Awf al-Harashiyya}} \n| children        = {{plainlist|\n*Muhammad\n*[[Abd al-Rahman ibn Ziyad|Abd al-Rahman]] \n*[[Ubayd Allah ibn Ziyad|Ubayd Allah]]\n*[[Salm ibn Ziyad|Salm]]\n*[[Abbad ibn Ziyad|Abbad]]\n*[[Yazid ibn Ziyad|Yazid]]\n*Abu Ubayda\n*Uthman{{sfn|Howard|1990|p=33, note 153}}\n*Umm Habib (daughter){{sfn|Morony|1976|p=57}}\n*Ramla (daughter)\n*Sakhra (daughter)}}\n}}\n\n'''Abu al-Mughira Ziyad ibn Abihi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0632\u064a\u0627\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0623\u0628\u064a\u0647|Ab\u016b al-Mugh\u012bra Ziy\u0101d ibn Ab\u012bhi}}; {{circa|622}} \u2013 673), also known as '''Ziyad ibn Abi Sufyan''' ({{lang-ar|\u0632\u064a\u0627\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0623\u0628\u064a \u0633\u0641\u064a\u0627\u0646|Ziy\u0101d ibn Ab\u012b Sufy\u0101n}}), was an administrator and statesman of the successive [[Rashidun Caliphate|Rashidun]] and [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad]] [[caliphate]]s in the mid-7th century. He served as the governor of [[Basra]] in 665\u2013670 and ultimately the first governor of [[History of Iraq#Middle Ages|Iraq]] and virtual viceroy of the eastern Caliphate between 670 and his death.\n\nZiyad's parentage is obscure, but he was raised among the [[Banu Thaqif]] in [[Ta'if]] and arrived with his adoptive tribesmen in Basra upon its foundation in 636 as the Muslim Arabs' springboard for the [[Muslim conquest of Persia|conquest of the Sasanian Empire]]. He was initially employed by the city's first governor, [[Utbah ibn Ghazwan|Utba ibn Ghazwan al-Mazini]], and was kept on as a scribe or secretary by his successors. Caliph [[Ali]] ({{reign|656|661}}) appointed Ziyad to [[Pars (Sasanian province)|Fars]] to suppress a local rebellion and he maintained his loyalty to Ali's caliphate after the latter's assassination in 661 and the subsequent rule of Ali's enemy, [[Mu'awiya I]] ({{reign|661|680}}). The latter ultimately overcame Ziyad's opposition, formally recognized him as his own paternal half-brother and appointed him governor of Basra. Ziyad's inaugural speech, in which he announced his carrot-and-stick policies to the city's turbulent population, is celebrated in Arab history for its eloquence. After the death of [[Kufa]]'s governor, Ziyad's mentor [[al-Mughira ibn Shu'ba]], Mu'awiya made Ziyad the first governor of a unified Iraqi province. He administratively reorganized the [[amsar|garrison cities]] and minted [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]]-style silver [[dirham]]s in his own name. He firmly established Arab power and recommenced conquests in the Caliphate's easternmost province of [[Greater Khorasan|Khurasan]] by relocating there 50,000 Arab soldiers and their families from Iraq and dispatching expeditionary forces against [[Tukharistan]], [[Balkh]] and [[Quhistan]]. Though the mass resettlement improved Iraq's economic and political conditions by siphoning off Arab tribal soldiers from the overcrowded garrisons and creating new opportunities for war spoils, the move had major ramifications for the Caliphate as the descendants of these Khurasani Arab troops formed the army that toppled the Umayyads in 750. \n\nZiyad died near Kufa in 673, but his sons [[Ubayd Allah ibn Ziyad|Ubayd Allah]], [[Abd al-Rahman ibn Ziyad|Abd al-Rahman]], [[Salm ibn Ziyad|Salm]], [[Abbad ibn Ziyad|Abbad]] and [[Yazid ibn Ziyad|Yazid]] went on to hold posts as governors or deputy governors of Iraq, Khurasan and [[Sistan|Sijistan]]. Ziyad was the subject of early Arabic biographies and is remembered in Arab history as one of the four great wise men of his era and as a highly skilled administrator and orator. His administration in Iraq served as a model for his successors.\n\n==Origins==\nZiyad was likely born in [[Ta'if]] in 622 or 623/24.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} His precise parentage is obscure, hence his frequent name in the sources as ''Ziy\u0101d ibn Ab\u012bhi'' (\"Ziyad son of his father\").{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}}{{sfn|Lynch|2018|page=1662}} He was the illegitimate son of a certain Sumayya, his father being unknown. The origins of Sumayya are also obscure. The 9th-century historians [[al-Baladhuri]] and [[Awana ibn al-Hakam]] both relate that she had been a slave living in [[Kashkar]], though the former asserts she belonged to a member of the [[Banu Yashkur]], a branch of the Arab tribe of [[Banu Bakr]], and the latter states she belonged to a Persian ''[[dehqan]]'' (landowning magnate). In the narrative of al-Baladhuri, Sumayya's Yashkuri owner embarked on the [[Hajj]] pilgrimage to [[Mecca]] seeking to cure his illness and was subsequently treated in Ta'if by [[al-Harith ibn Kalada]], a physician from the [[Banu Thaqif|Thaqif]] clan resident in the city; as a reward for his services, Ibn Kalada was gifted Sumayya. In Awana's narrative, Sumayya was given to Ibn Kalada by the Persian ''dehqan'' after he treated him. In any case, she was ultimately given to Ubayd, a [[R\u00fbm|Greek]] or [[Arameans|Syrian]] slave belonging to Ibn Kalada's wife. Though Ziyad alludes to his Persian origin in a poem, his family claimed that Sumayya was not a slave, but the daughter of a certain al-A'war from the Zayd Manat clan of the Arab tribe of [[Banu Tamim]].{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}\n\n==Early career in Basra==\n[[File:Basra late 19th early 20th century.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|A creek in Basra in the early 20th century. Ziyad began his career in Basra in 636 and served as its governor between 665 and his death in 673]]\n\nDuring the reign of Caliph [[Abu Bakr]] ({{reign|632|634}}), Ziyad embraced Islam,{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} which \"opened the world to him\", according to historian [[Julius Wellhausen]].{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=120}} He later became one of the first settlers of the Arab garrison town of [[Basra]].{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=119}} Before the city's founding in 638, the Muslim troops fighting on the Iraqi front used as their military camp the ruined Persian village on the site.{{sfn|Pellat|1960|p=1085}} Ziyad arrived there with the sons of Ibn Kalada, [[Nafi ibn al-Harith|Nafi]] and [[Nufay ibn al-Harith|Abu Bakra Nufay]].{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} The latter's family gained preeminence in the city, having acquired large landholdings there.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=120}} Abu Bakra's brother-in-law [[Utbah ibn Ghazwan|Utba ibn Ghazwan al-Mazini]] had established the initial camp at Basra in 635 and was the founder and first governor of the city.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}{{sfn|Pellat|1960|p=1085}} The administrative skills of Ziyad became apparent from the time of his adolescence and Utba charged him with minor tasks in the Basran ''[[divan|d\u012bw\u0101n]]'' (bureaucracy) during the reign of Caliph [[Umar]] ({{reign|634|644}}).{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} In 635, Utba tasked him with distributing to the Arab troops the war spoils from the capture of [[al-Ubulla]] (Apologos), a town immediately east of Basra.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}{{sfn|Donner|1981|p=415}} According to the modern historian Isaac Hasson, Ziyad \"distinguished himself as an intelligent and open-minded secretary, who was devoted to his master and to public service ... he showed an unusual aptitude for accounting and had an excellent command of [[epistle|epistolary]] art\".{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} His skills and his assignment by Basra's military governor [[Abu Musa al-Ash'ari]] as his acting replacement while he was on a military campaign gained the attention of Caliph Umar.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} He brought Ziyad to [[Medina]], the center of the nascent Muslim state, where he further tested his skills; Ziyad's performance earned him a reward of 1,000 silver [[dirham]]s by Umar, which he used to purchase the freedom of his mother or his stepfather Ubayd.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} Soon after his return to Basra, Ziyad was made Utba's ''[[katib|k\u0101tib]]'' (scribe or secretary).{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}\n\nAfter Utba's death, Ziyad continued his service as ''k\u0101tib'' under his successors Abu Musa al-Ash'ari and [[al-Mughira ibn Shu'ba]], a member of the Thaqif who became Ziyad's mentor.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}}{{sfn|Donner|1981|p=415}}{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=119}} When al-Mughira was recalled by Umar to Medina in 638 due to charges of adultery by three accusers, including Abu Bakra Nufay and a certain Shibl ibn Ma'bad al-Bajali, both of whom were Ziyad's maternal half-brothers, Ziyad was also recalled to give his own testimony.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} His statement was partial toward al-Mughira and as a result, the charges were dismissed and the accusers were flogged.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} During the reign of Caliph [[Uthman]] ({{reign|644|656}}), Ziyad served the caliph's appointee to Basra, [[Abdallah ibn Amir|Abd Allah ibn Amir]].{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}\n\nUthman's successor [[Ali]] ({{reign|656|661}}) appointed [[Abd Allah ibn Abbas]] governor of Basra and entrusted Ziyad with collection of the province's ''[[kharaj|khar\u0101j]]'' (land tax) and supervision of the treasury.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}}{{sfn|Madelung|1997|pp=220, 271}} According to Hasson, \"Ali's appreciation of Ziyad's talents were so great\" that he mandated Ibn Abbas heed Ziyad's counsel.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} When Ibn Abbas left Basra in 657 to accompany Ali at the [[Battle of Siffin]] against the governor of Syria, [[Muawiyah I|Mu'awiya ibn Abi Sufyan]], he left Ziyad as his acting governor.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|pp=277, 280}} During this period, he stamped out an uprising by the Banu Tamim, a major military tribal faction in the city, with critical assistance from another Basran faction, the [[Azd]].{{sfn|Madelung|1997|pp=280\u2013282}} \n\nAfter Ali returned from Siffin, his appointee to the district of [[Pars (Sasanian province)|Fars]], Sahl ibn Hunayf, was ousted by its inhabitants, after which he dispatched Ziyad.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} The people of Fars were satisfied with Ziyad's leadership and he was able to collect the district's ''khar\u0101j''.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} He remained in Fars through the remainder of Ali's rule, which ended with the caliph's assassination in 661 and the foundation of the [[Umayyad Caliphate]] under Mu'awiya.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} Afterward, he remained headquartered in a fortress in the vicinity of [[Istakhr]]. Of Ali's appointees, he held out the longest from recognizing Mu'awiya's caliphate.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=120}}{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=325}} Mu'awiya's agent, [[Busr ibn Abi Artat]], pressured Ziyad by capturing and threatening to kill three of his sons in Basra.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=120}}{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=325}} Ziyad's half-brother Abu Bakra interceded with Mu'awiya and Ziyad's sons were released.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=326}} He finally surrendered to Mu'awiya's rule in 662/63 after the intercession of al-Mughira, who Mu'awiya had appointed governor of [[Kufa]], the other main Arab garrison town of Iraq.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}}{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=121}} In the deal reached, the revenues from Fars owed to the caliphal treasury were split between Ziyad and al-Mughira, which Mu'awiya ignored.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=121}} Ziyad moved to Kufa and maintained intimate ties with al-Mughira and his family.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=122}}\n\n==Governor of Basra==\n[[File:Medieval Basra Map.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|Map of medieval Basra, showing Ziyad's divisions of the city into fifths along Arab tribal factional lines: [[Abd al-Qays]], [[Banu Tamim|Tamim]], [[Qays|Ahl al-Aliya]], [[Banu Bakr|Bakr]] and [[Azd]]]]\n\nMu'awiya formally recognized Ziyad as a son of his father [[Abu Sufyan]]. The motion was initiated when Ziyad sought clarification from the caliph about rumors of Abu Sufyan's biological paternity.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} According to Wellhausen, Mu'awiya summoned Ziyad to Damascus and recognized him as his paternal half-brother, \"so as to bind him in this way absolutely to himself and to his family\".{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=121\u2013122}} The decision was seen as scandalous by the [[Umayyad dynasty|Umayyad ruling family]].{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=121}} Mu'awiya's son [[Yazid I|Yazid]] and members from other branches of the clan, namely the extended family of [[Marwan I|Marwan ibn al-Hakam]] in Medina and Abd Allah ibn Amir, the governor of Basra, protested or threatened action against the decision.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} Ibn Amir and the Marwanids were silenced as a result of threats of force or bribes.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} Yazid's relations with Ziyad remained strained and satirical poetic verses about the event were spread by Marwan's brother Abd al-Rahman.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=121\u2013122}} Muslim scholars generally viewed the episode as one of Mu'awiya's most disreputable actions.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=332, note 55}}\n\nRealizing that Ziyad \"had both the abilities and the all-important local connections to be his right-hand man in Basra\", Mu'awiya appointed him governor of the province, according to the historian [[Hugh N. Kennedy]].{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}} He entered office in June or July 665, issuing an inaugural carrot-and-stick speech to Basra's restless population.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}} According to Hasson it was \"considered a masterpiece of eloquence\".{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} Wellhausen describes it as \"celebrated\" and the one which was called a \"[speech] without a preface\"{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=122}} because it skipped the traditional introductions praising God and blessing the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]].{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}} The speech is translated as follows: <blockquote>Ye are putting relationship before religion, ye are excusing and sheltering your criminals, and tearing down the protecting laws sanctified by Islam. Beware of prowling by night; I will kill every one who is found at night in the streets. Beware of the arbitrary summons of relationship; I will cut out the tongue of every one who raises the cry. Whoever pushes anyone into the water, whoever sets fire to another's house, whoever breaks into a house, whoever opens a grave, him will I punish for it. I make every family responsible for those belonging to it. Hatred towards myself I do not punish, but only crime. Many who are terrified at my coming will be glad of my presence, and many who are building their hopes upon it will be undeceived. I rule you with the authority of God and care for your maintenance out of the wealth of God. From you I demand obedience, and ye can demand from me justice. In whatsoever I fall short, three things there are in which I shall not be lacking: at any time I shall be ready to listen to anyone; I shall pay you your pension at the proper time, and I shall not send you to war too far away or keep you in the field overlong. Do not let yourselves be carried away by your hatred and wrath against me ; it would go ill with you if ye did. Many heads do I see tottering; let each man see to it that his own remains on his shoulders!{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=122\u2013123}}</blockquote>  \n\nA number of punitive measures along the lines of those cited in his speech were taken by Ziyad at the start of his term and largely gained for him the Basrans' respect.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=123}} He established unprecedented levels of security in the city, its Iranian dependencies to the east, i.e. Fars and [[Kerman]], and the [[Arabian Desert]] to the south. The [[Kharijites]] of Basra, many of whom were concerned more with banditry than politics, submitted to his authority.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=123\u2013124}} Under Ziyad, Basra began to take shape as a proper Islamic city.{{sfn|Pellat|1960|p=1085}} His rule saw the crude mud bricks of the city's homes replaced by more durable baked bricks and he built a [[congregational mosque]] and residential palace.{{sfn|Pellat|1960|p=1085}} In the words of the historian [[Charles Pellat]], Ziyad, \"to a certain degree, [may] be considered as the artisan of the town's prosperity\".{{sfn|Pellat|1960|p=1085}} His effective rule cemented Mu'awiya's confidence in him.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}} In the same year that Ziyad was appointed to Basra, the province of [[Eastern Arabia|Bahrayn]] (eastern Arabia) and its dependency, the [[Al-Yamamah|Yamama]] (central Arabia), were attached to Ziyad's governorship.{{sfn|Baloch|1946|p=258}}\n\n==Viceroy of Iraq and the east==\nAfter the death of al-Mughira in 670, Kufa and its dependencies were attached to Ziyad's governorship, making him the practical viceroy over Iraq and the eastern half of the Caliphate.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}}{{sfn|Hawting|2000|p=41}} He was the first to serve as the dual governor of Kufa and Basra and divided his residence between the two towns.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} In the winter he stayed in Basra and left [[Amr ibn Hurayth]] as his deputy in Kufa, while he resided in Kufa in the summer, leaving [[Samura ibn Jundab]] as his deputy in Basra.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} His strong grip in Kufa marked a shift from al-Mughira's hands-off approach.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}} A source of disturbance for him in Kufa was the agitation of the [[Alids]],{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} partisans of Caliph Ali, led by [[Hujr ibn Adi|Hujr ibn Adi al-Kindi]], who disapproved of Umayyad rule and led the first open calls for the caliphate to be held by Ali's progeny.{{sfn|Hawting|2000|p=41}} Though al-Mughira tolerated Hujr, Ziyad issued a number of dire warnings to cease his open dissent.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} He succeeded in turning most of Hujr's supporters among the Kufan troops against him.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}}{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=124\u2013125}} In 671, he had Hujr and thirteen of his loyalists arrested and sent to Damascus for punishment, where six, including Hujr, were executed in [[Adra, Syria|Adra]] for their refusal to renounce support for the Alids.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=337}} One of the men, Abd al-Rahman ibn Hassan al-Anazi, who was spared by Mu'awiya later insulted the caliph after refusing his invocation to condemn Ali and was sent back to Ziyad, who had him buried alive as punishment.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=338}}\n\nTo end the chaos in the ''[[amsar|am\u1e63ar]]'' (garrisons) of Basra and Kufa, Ziyad administratively reformed the two towns.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} From the reign of Caliph Umar, their garrisons consisted of soldiers from different tribes who were grouped together for the distribution of military stipends.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} There were seven such tribal groups in Kufa and Basra and at the head of each group was a chieftain chosen by its members who served as their representative to the government.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|pp=520\u2013521}}{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=125}} Gradually, this system had become economically inefficient and politically turbulent.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|pp=520\u2013521}} There was no control on Arab immigration into the ''am\u1e63ar'', resulting in overpopulation and in turn, increased competition over fewer resources.{{sfn|Hinds|1993|p=266}} Ziyad thus resolved to form larger divisions by unifying related clans and personally appointing their leader, which resulted in Kufa's reorganization into quarters and Basra into fifths.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} This measure enabled easier control of the two towns' inhabitants.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} Ziyad undertook further reforms in Kufa and Basra, including regularizing the timely payment of stipends, embarking on agricultural development schemes, including canal digging, and minting [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]]-style dirhams that bore his name as \"Ziyad ibn Abi Sufyan\".{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}}\n\n===Consolidation of Khurasan===\n[[File:Transoxiana 8th century.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|Map of early medieval Central Asia with [[Greater Khorasan|Khurasan]], where Ziyad settled 50,000 Arab troops and their families, and [[Balkh]] and [[Tukharistan]], where Ziyad's general led expeditions]]\n\nZiyad's authority extended to [[Greater Khorasan|Khurasan]] and [[Sistan|Sijistan]], the far eastern regions of the Caliphate which were considered dependencies of the Basra garrison.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} The Arab conquests of these areas in the 640s and 650s were akin to raids and did not firmly establish the Caliphate's power.{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=15}} Moreover, the political instability of the final years of Uthman's caliphate and the First Muslim Civil War saw local revolts which further weakened Arab authority.{{sfn|Shaban|1979|pp=26\u201327}} In 655, the Sasanian prince [[Peroz III]], backed by the army of [[Tukharistan]], attempted to reassert Persian power.{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=16}} Under previous caliphs, the vast region had been experimentally divided into separate provinces under the leadership of Arab tribal chiefs.{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=16}} Governance was largely left to local princes.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=86}} Fearing a Persian resurgence, which a fragmentary division of Khurasan could afford, Ziyad centralized the administration of the province in the small Arab garrison at Merv.{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=16}} \n\nTo relieve Basra's fiscal pressures, Ziyad recommenced the [[Muslim conquest of Transoxiana|Muslim conquests in Central Asia]].{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}}{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=86}} He organized the Arab military presence in Khurasan.{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=16}} In 667, he dispatched an army to the region under his lieutenant general [[al-Hakam ibn Amr al-Ghifari]].{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=16}}{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=86}} The latter conquered lower Tukharistan and [[Gharchistan]] and temporarily crossed the [[Oxus]] river into [[Transoxiana]], forcing Peroz to withdraw into [[Tang dynasty|Tang China]].{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=16}} Meanwhile, Ziyad's removal of dead soldiers and input of new recruits to the Iraqi army registers led to numerous tribesmen being taken off the payrolls.{{sfn|Shaban|1979|pp=31\u201332}} He dispatched 50,000 Arab soldiers and their families from Basra and Kufa to permanently settle in the Merv oasis of Khurasan.{{sfn|Shaban|1979|p=32}} The resettlement of these troops may have been a means \"to defuse possibly dangerous developments\" relating to the Arab tribal influx in the two garrison towns, according to the historian [[Gerald Hawting]].{{sfn|Hawting|2000|p=41}} As a result, the Merv oasis became home to the largest concentration of Muslims outside of the [[Fertile Crescent]].{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=86}} \n\nAl-Hakam's successor, [[Ghalib ibn Abd Allah al-Laythi]], was less successful in subduing Tukharistan and Ziyad sent another of his lieutenants, [[Rabi ibn Ziyad al-Harithi]], to stamp out the revolts in the conquered areas in 670/71.{{sfn|Shaban|1979|p=32}}{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=16}} Rabi proceeded to secure the capitulation of [[Balkh]], whose inhabitants had revolted against Arab rule, in a treaty and then destroyed the army of the [[Hephthalites|Hepthalite]] princes in [[Quhistan]].{{sfn|Shaban|1979|p=32}} In 673, Rabi's son Abd Allah extended Arab rule to the western banks of the Oxus and established tributary agreements with the fortress towns of [[Amul]] and [[Zamm]].{{sfn|Shaban|1979|p=32}} To solidify the territorial gains and supply the manpower for further conquests Ziyad intended for the Arab troops, initially concentrated in the Merv oasis, to colonize other parts of Khurasan.{{sfn|Shaban|1979|pp=32\u201334}} They were ultimately distributed between five regional garrisons under Ziyad's successors.{{sfn|Shaban|1979|p=34}}{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=17}}\n\n==Legacy and assessment==\nZiyad died in the village of al-Thawiyya near Kufa on 23 August 673.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=126}} He was buried in a cemetery there that contained the graves of several Qurayshites and left an inheritance of 10,000 silver dirhams.{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=128}} During his governorship of Kufa in 675\u2013678, [[al-Dahhak ibn Qays al-Fihri]] visited Ziyad's grave and recited an elegy: <blockquote>If nobility and Islam ever immortalized a human being, <br /> They would certainly immortalize you.{{sfn|Boullata|2011|p=164}}</blockquote> A year after his death, Mu'awiya appointed Ziyad's son [[Ubayd Allah ibn Ziyad|Ubayd Allah]] as governor of Khurasan and then Basra. {{sfn|Robinson|2000|p=763}} Under Mu'awiya's son and successor, Caliph Yazid I ({{reign|680|683}}), the governorship of Kufa was also handed to Ubayd Allah.{{sfn|Robinson|2000|p=763}} Ziyad's sons [[Abd al-Rahman ibn Ziyad|Abd al-Rahman]] and [[Salm ibn Ziyad|Salm]] served successively as governors of Khurasan in 678\u2013680 and 680\u2013683/84,{{sfn|Morony|1987|pp=199, 207}}{{sfn|Bosworth|1995|p=169}} and two other sons, [[Abbad ibn Ziyad|Abbad]] and [[Yazid ibn Ziyad|Yazid]], served successively as governors of Sijistan in 673\u2013680/81 and 680/81.{{sfn|Zetterst\u00e9en|1960|p=5}}{{sfn|Bosworth|1968|p=44}} The Thaqif, which had maintained close ties with the Umayyads since the pre-Islamic era and played an integral role in the Muslim conquest of Iraq, provided the Umayyad dynasty with a series of viceroys in Iraq, including al-Mughira, Ziyad, Ubayd Allah and [[al-Hajjaj ibn Yusuf]] ({{reign|694|714}}), and the Muslim traditional sources devote more attention to them than the caliphs on whose behalf they ruled.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=113\u2013114}} Along with his mentor al-Mughira, Ziyad and his family were part of what \"some must have seen as a Thaqafi mafia\" controlling Iraq and the east, according to Kennedy.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=86}} \n\nAmong \"the most gifted governors of the Umayyad era\", Ziyad \"had a good understanding of his task as governor, and had a great influence on his successors concerning the conception of the duties of rulers\", according to Hasson.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} According to Kennedy, Ziyad's settlement of Iraqi Arab troops in Khurasan had \"extremely important consequences for Islamic history\" as the descendants of those settlers,{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=86}} who were known as ''ahl Khur\u0101s\u0101n'',{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} [[Abbasid Revolution|ultimately destroyed]] the Umayyad Caliphate as part of the [[Abbasid Caliphate|Abbasid]] army in 750.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=86}} The execution of Hujr and his six partisans, all of whom had been prominent men in their own right, also led to deep-seated resentment among their Kufan kinsmen.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=124\u2013125}} The incident would serve as a harbinger for future pro-Alid risings.{{sfn|Hawting|2000|p=41}} The death of Hujr represented the first political execution in Islamic history,{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} and he and his companions are viewed as martyrs by [[Shia Muslim]]s.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=125}} Ziyad was alleged to have ordered cruel acts against some Alid partisans, including crucifixions.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}}\n\nInterest in Ziyad's biography emerged early on among the traditional Muslim historians, with works written about him by [[Abu Mikhnaf]] (d. 774), [[Hisham ibn al-Kalbi]] (d. 819) and Abd al-Aziz ibn Yahya al-Jaludi (d. 943).{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} He is considered a highly skilled orator among Arabs, with his inaugural speech and fragments of other speeches and sayings cited in [[Islamic literature]] and Arabic rhetoric, polemics and histories.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} He is counted alongside Mu'awiya, al-Mughira and [[Amr ibn al-As]], the conqueror and governor of Egypt, as one of the four ''duh\u0101t'' (i.e. \"shrewds\") among the Arab statesmen of his era.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} According to the medieval Syrian historian [[Ibn Asakir]] (d. 1176), Ziyad had expert knowledge of the [[Qur'an]], its tenets and [[fiqh|Islamic jurisprudence]].{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} A medieval Basran historian, Muhammad ibn Imran al-Abdi, related that Ziyad respected and enjoyed listening to the [[hadith]]s about Umar and proclaimed about them: \"This is the truth we hear! This is the [[sunnah|sunna]]!\"{{sfn|Hakim|2008|p=23}} Ziyad is credited by a number of sources for transmitting sayings by the Islamic prophet Muhammad through Umar as the original transmitter.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} In 777 the Abbasid authorities stripped Ziyad's descendants of their status as official members of the Quraysh (the tribe to which the Umayyads and Abbasids belonged) in the ''d\u012bw\u0101n'' rolls, which entitled them to relatively high pensions, and declared them part of Thaqif, whose members were paid less.{{sfn|Tritton|1954|p=171}} At some point afterward, they were reinstated as Quraysh as a result of bribing government officials.{{sfn|Tritton|1954|p=171}}\n\n==Family==\nZiyad had numerous wives and ''[[umm walad|ummahat awlad]]'' (slave women who bore children; sing. ''umm walad'').{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=121}} He had twenty sons and twenty-three daughters, most of whom were the children of ''ummahat awlad''.{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=121}} From his first wife Mu'adha bint Sakhr of the [[Banu Uqayl]] tribe Ziyad had four sons, including Muhammad and Abd al-Rahman, who respectively married daughters of Caliph Mu'awiya I and the latter's brother [[Utba ibn Abi Sufyan|Utba]].{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=121}} His other Arab wives were Lubaba bint Awf al-Harashiyya, the daughter of a Basran noble, whose brother Zurara was a prominent Muslim jurist and one-time [[qadi]] (Islamic head judge) of Basra on Ziyad's behalf; an unnamed daughter of al-Qa'qa ibn Ma'bad ibn Zurara, a chieftain of the Darim clan of the [[Banu Tamim]] tribe who was credited for leading his tribe's first delegation to the Islamic prophet Muhammad; an unnamed daughter of Muhajir ibn Hakim ibn Taliq ibn Sufyan, a fifth-generation descendant of the Umayyad clan's progenitor [[Umayya ibn Abd Shams]]; and an unnamed woman from the [[Banu Khuza'a|Khuza'a]] tribe.{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=121}} Ziyad was also married for a time to a Sasanian Persian princess, Marjana (or Manjana), who mothered his son Ubayd Allah; she later remarried a Persian commander of Ziyad called Shiruyah al-Uswari.{{sfn|Zakeri|1995|p=116}}\n\nZiyad's daughter Ramla was a wife of the Umayyad prince [[Umayya ibn Abdallah ibn Khalid ibn Asid|Umayya]], son of Ziyad's deputy governor of Fars province or its [[Ardashir-Khwarrah|Ardashir-Khurrah]] district and later his deputy governor of Kufa, [[Abdallah ibn Khalid ibn Asid]], who led Ziyad's funeral prayers and served as Kufa's governor until 675.{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=123}} Ziyad had successively appointed Umayya as the deputy governor of [[Khuzistan]] and al-Ubulla.{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=123}} Ziyad's daughter Sakhra was married to a noble of the Qurayshite [[Makhzum]] clan, Ubaydallah ibn Abd al-Rahman ibn al-Harith, a great-grandson of [[Hisham ibn al-Mughira]].{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=123}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite journal |last1=Baloch |first1=Nabi Bakhsh Khan |authorlink=Nabi Bakhsh Khan Baloch |title=The Probable Date of the First Arab Expeditions to India |journal=Islamic Culture |date=July 1946 |volume=20 |issue=3 |pages=250\u2013266 |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.92019/page/n324 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bosworth |first1=C. E. |authorlink=Clifford Edmund Bosworth |title=S\u012bst\u0101n under the Arabs: From the Islamic Conquest to the Rise of the \u1e62aff\u0101rids (30\u2013250, 651\u2013864) |date=1968 |publisher=Istituto italiano per il Medio ed Estremo Oriente |location=Rome |oclc=956878036 |ref=harv}}\n*{{EI2 |article=Salm b. Ziy\u0101d b. Ab\u012bhi |last=Bosworth |first=C. E. |volume=8 |page=997}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Boullata |first1=Issa J. |title=The Unique Necklace: Al-'Iqd Al-Farid, Volume 3 |date=2011 |publisher=Garnet Publishing |location=Reading |isbn=978-1-85964-240-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dQ9KCcDUBT4C |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Donner |first1=Fred M. |authorlink=Fred M. Donner |title=The Early Islamic Conquests |date=1981 |publisher=Princeton University Press |location=Princeton |url={{Gbook|l5__AwAAQBAJ|plainurl=y}} |ref=harv}}\n*{{The Arab Conquests in Central Asia}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Fariq |first1=K. A. |title=Ziy\u0101d b. Ab\u012bh |date=1966 |publisher=Asia Publishing House |location=London |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zLtWAAAAMAAJ |oclc=581630755 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Hakim |first1=Avraham |title=\u02bfUmar b. al-\u1e2aa\u1e6d\u1e6d\u0101b: L'autorit\u00e9 religieuse et morale |journal=Arabica |date=January 2008 |volume=55 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201334 |ref=harv |publisher=Brill |language=French|jstor=25162264 |doi=10.1163/157005808X289296 }}\n*{{EI2 |article=Ziy\u0101d b. Ab\u012bhi |last=Hasson |first=I. |authorlink= |volume=11 |pages=519\u2013522}}\n*{{The First Dynasty of Islam|edition=Second}}\n*{{EI2 |article=Mu\u02bf\u0101wiya I b. Ab\u012b Sufy\u0101n |last=Hinds |first=M. |authorlink=Martin Hinds |volume=7 |pages=263\u2013268}}\n*{{The Prophet and the Age of the Caliphates|edition=Second}}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=19 |url={{Gbook||plainurl=y}}}}\n*{{ODLA|last=Lynch|first=Ryan J.|title=Ziyad b. Abi Sufyan (Ziyad b. Abihi)|url=https://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780198662778.001.0001/acref-9780198662778-e-5141?rskey=y0sSQ0&result=1|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Madelung |first1=Wilferd |authorlink=Wilferd Madelung |title=The Succession to Muhammad: A Study of the Early Caliphate |date=1997 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |isbn=0-521-56181-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2QKBUwBUWWkC |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Morony |first1=Michael |title=The Effects of the Muslim Conquest on the Persian Population of Iraq |journal=Iran |date=1976 |volume=14 |pages=41\u201359 |ref=harv|jstor=4300543 |doi=10.2307/4300543 }}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=18 |url={{Gbook|9DHhZ5Wwo_YC|plainurl=y}}}}\n*{{EI2 |article=Al-Ba\u1e63ra \u2014 Ba\u1e63ra until the Mongol conquest (656/1258) |last=Pellat |first=Ch. |authorlink=Charles Pellat |volume=1 |pages=1085\u20131086}}\n*{{EI2 |article=\u02bfUbayd All\u0101h b. Ziy\u0101d |last=Robinson |first=C. F. |authorlink=Chase F. Robinson |volume=10 |pages=763\u2013764}}\n*{{cite book |title=The 'Abb\u0101sid Revolution |first=M. A. |last=Shaban |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |year=1979 |isbn=0-521-29534-3 |url={{Gbook|1_03AAAAIAAJ|plainurl=y}} |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Tritton |first1=A. S. |title=Notes and Communications |journal=Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies |date=1954 |volume=16 |issue=1 |pages=170\u2013172 |url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/608915 |ref=harv}}\n*{{The Arab Kingdom and its Fall}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Zakeri |first1=Mohsen |title=Sasanid Soldiers in Early Muslim Society: The Origins of 'Ayy\u0101r\u0101n and Futuwwa |date=1995 |publisher=Harassowitz Verlag |location=Wiesbaden |isbn=3-447-03652-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VfYnu5F20coC&pg=PA116 |ref=harv}}\n*{{EI2 |article=\u02bfAbb\u0101d b. Ziy\u0101d |last=Zetterst\u00e9en |first=K. V. |authorlink=Karl Vilhelm Zetterst\u00e9en |volume=1 |page=5}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=Governor of [[Basra]]|before=[[Abd Allah ibn Amir]]|after=Office merged into governorship of Iraq|years=665&ndash;670}}\n{{succession box|title=Governor of Iraq|before=Office established|after=[[Samura ibn Jundab]] (Basra) <br /> [[Abdallah ibn Khalid ibn Asid]] ([[Kufa]])|years=670&ndash;673}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:622 births]]\n[[Category:673 deaths]]\n[[Category:7th-century Umayyad people]]\n[[Category:Banu Thaqif]]\n[[Category:Generals of the Umayyad Caliphate]]\n[[Category:People of the Muslim conquest of Persia]]\n[[Category:People of the Rashidun Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Umayyad governors of Basra]]\n[[Category:Umayyad governors of Iraq]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name            = Ziyad ibn Abihi\n| image           = Arab-Sasanian Dirham in the name of Ziyad ibn Abi Sufyan.jpg\n| image_size      = 250\n| alt             = \n| caption         = Silver ''[[dirham]]'' following [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]] motives, struck in the name of \"Ziyad ibn Abi Sufyan\"\n| birth_date      = 622\n| birth_place     = \n| death_date      = 673\n| death_place     = \n| monarch1        = [[Mu'awiya I]]\n| office1         = [[List of Umayyad Governors of Iraq|Umayyad governor of Basra]]\n| term1           = June/July 665\u2013670\n| predecessor1    = Al-Harith ibn Abd Allah al-Azdi{{efn|Al-Harith ibn Abd Allah al-Azdi served four months as governor of Basra and had been appointed effectively as a placeholder in between the dismissal of [[Abd Allah ibn Amir]] and the appointment of Ziyad.{{sfn|Morony|1987|page=76}}}}\n| successor1      = \n| monarch2        = Mu'awiya I\n| office2         = [[List of Umayyad Governors of Iraq|Umayyad governor of Iraq]]\n| term2           = 670\u2013673\n| predecessor2    = ''Post established'' \n| successor2      = [[Abdallah ibn Khalid ibn Asid]] (in Kufa) <br /> Samura ibn Jundab al-Fazari (in Basra)\n| parents         = Sumayya (mother)\n| spouse          = {{plainlist|\n*Mu'adha bint Sakhr al-Uqayliyya \n*Marjana \n*Bint Muhajir ibn Hakim ibn Taliq \n*Bint Qa'qa ibn Ma'bad ibn Zurara al-Darimiyya \n*Lubaba bint Awf al-Harashiyya}} \n| children        = {{plainlist|\n*Muhammad\n*[[Abd al-Rahman ibn Ziyad|Abd al-Rahman]] \n*[[Ubayd Allah ibn Ziyad|Ubayd Allah]]\n*[[Salm ibn Ziyad|Salm]]\n*[[Abbad ibn Ziyad|Abbad]]\n*[[Yazid ibn Ziyad|Yazid]]\n*Abu Ubayda\n*Uthman{{sfn|Howard|1990|p=33, note 153}}\n*Umm Habib (daughter){{sfn|Morony|1976|p=57}}\n*Ramla (daughter)\n*Sakhra (daughter)}}\n}}\n\n'''Abu al-Mughira Ziyad ibn Abihi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0632\u064a\u0627\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0623\u0628\u064a\u0647|Ab\u016b al-Mugh\u012bra Ziy\u0101d ibn Ab\u012bhi}}; {{circa|622}} \u2013 673), also known as '''Ziyad ibn Abi Sufyan''' ({{lang-ar|\u0632\u064a\u0627\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0623\u0628\u064a \u0633\u0641\u064a\u0627\u0646|Ziy\u0101d ibn Ab\u012b Sufy\u0101n}}), was an administrator and statesman of the successive [[Rashidun Caliphate|Rashidun]] and [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad]] [[caliphate]]s in the mid-7th century. He served as the governor of [[Basra]] in 665\u2013670 and ultimately the first governor of [[History of Iraq#Middle Ages|Iraq]] and virtual viceroy of the eastern Caliphate between 670 and his death.\n\nZiyad's parentage is obscure, but he was raised among the [[Banu Thaqif]] in [[Ta'if]] and arrived with his adoptive tribesmen in Basra upon its foundation in 636 as the Muslim Arabs' springboard for the [[Muslim conquest of Persia|conquest of the Sasanian Empire]]. He was initially employed by the city's first governor, [[Utbah ibn Ghazwan|Utba ibn Ghazwan al-Mazini]], and was kept on as a scribe or secretary by his successors. Caliph [[Ali]] ({{reign|656|661}}) appointed Ziyad to [[Pars (Sasanian province)|Fars]] to suppress a local rebellion and he maintained his loyalty to Ali's caliphate after the latter's assassination in 661 and the subsequent rule of Ali's enemy, [[Mu'awiya I]] ({{reign|661|680}}). The latter ultimately overcame Ziyad's opposition, formally recognized him as his own paternal half-brother and appointed him governor of Basra. Ziyad's inaugural speech, in which he announced his carrot-and-stick policies to the city's turbulent population, is celebrated in Arab history for its eloquence. After the death of [[Kufa]]'s governor, Ziyad's mentor [[al-Mughira ibn Shu'ba]], Mu'awiya made Ziyad the first governor of a unified Iraqi province. He administratively reorganized the [[amsar|garrison cities]] and minted [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]]-style silver [[dirham]]s in his own name. He firmly established Arab power and recommenced conquests in the Caliphate's easternmost province of [[Greater Khorasan|Khurasan]] by relocating there 50,000 Arab soldiers and their families from Iraq and dispatching expeditionary forces against [[Tukharistan]], [[Balkh]] and [[Quhistan]]. Though the mass resettlement improved Iraq's economic and political conditions by siphoning off Arab tribal soldiers from the overcrowded garrisons and creating new opportunities for war spoils, the move had major ramifications for the Caliphate as the descendants of these Khurasani Arab troops formed the army that toppled the Umayyads in 750. \n\nZiyad died near Kufa in 673, but his sons [[Ubayd Allah ibn Ziyad|Ubayd Allah]], [[Abd al-Rahman ibn Ziyad|Abd al-Rahman]], [[Salm ibn Ziyad|Salm]], [[Abbad ibn Ziyad|Abbad]] and [[Yazid ibn Ziyad|Yazid]] went on to hold posts as governors or deputy governors of Iraq, Khurasan and [[Sistan|Sijistan]]. Ziyad was the subject of early Arabic biographies and is remembered in Arab history as one of the four great wise men of his era and as a highly skilled administrator and orator. His administration in Iraq served as a model for his successors.\n\n==Origins==\nZiyad was likely born in [[Ta'if]] in 622 or 623/24.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} His precise parentage is obscure, hence his frequent name in the sources as ''Ziy\u0101d ibn Ab\u012bhi'' (\"Ziyad son of his father\").{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}}{{sfn|Lynch|2018|page=1662}} He was the illegitimate son of a certain Sumayya, his father being unknown. The origins of Sumayya are also obscure. The 9th-century historians [[al-Baladhuri]] and [[Awana ibn al-Hakam]] both relate that she had been a slave living in [[Kashkar]], though the former asserts she belonged to a member of the [[Banu Yashkur]], a branch of the Arab tribe of [[Banu Bakr]], and the latter states she belonged to a Persian ''[[dehqan]]'' (landowning magnate). In the narrative of al-Baladhuri, Sumayya's Yashkuri owner embarked on the [[Hajj]] pilgrimage to [[Mecca]] seeking to cure his illness and was subsequently treated in Ta'if by [[al-Harith ibn Kalada]], a physician from the [[Banu Thaqif|Thaqif]] clan resident in the city; as a reward for his services, Ibn Kalada was gifted Sumayya. In Awana's narrative, Sumayya was given to Ibn Kalada by the Persian ''dehqan'' after he treated him. In any case, she was ultimately given to Ubayd, a [[R\u00fbm|Greek]] or [[Arameans|Syrian]] slave belonging to Ibn Kalada's wife. Though Ziyad alludes to his Persian origin in a poem, his family claimed that Sumayya was not a slave, but the daughter of a certain al-A'war from the Zayd Manat clan of the Arab tribe of [[Banu Tamim]].{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}\n\n==Early career in Basra==\n[[File:Basra late 19th early 20th century.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|A creek in Basra in the early 20th century. Ziyad began his career in Basra in 636 and served as its governor between 665 and his death in 673]]\n\nDuring the reign of Caliph [[Abu Bakr]] ({{reign|632|634}}), Ziyad embraced Islam,{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} which \"opened the world to him\", according to historian [[Julius Wellhausen]].{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=120}} He later became one of the first settlers of the Arab garrison town of [[Basra]].{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=119}} Before the city's founding in 638, the Muslim troops fighting on the Iraqi front used as their military camp the ruined Persian village on the site.{{sfn|Pellat|1960|p=1085}} Ziyad arrived there with the sons of Ibn Kalada, [[Nafi ibn al-Harith|Nafi]] and [[Nufay ibn al-Harith|Abu Bakra Nufay]].{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} The latter's family gained preeminence in the city, having acquired large landholdings there.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=120}} Abu Bakra's brother-in-law [[Utbah ibn Ghazwan|Utba ibn Ghazwan al-Mazini]] had established the initial camp at Basra in 635 and was the founder and first governor of the city.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}{{sfn|Pellat|1960|p=1085}} The administrative skills of Ziyad became apparent from the time of his adolescence and Utba charged him with minor tasks in the Basran ''[[divan|d\u012bw\u0101n]]'' (bureaucracy) during the reign of Caliph [[Umar]] ({{reign|634|644}}).{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} In 635, Utba tasked him with distributing to the Arab troops the war spoils from the capture of [[al-Ubulla]] (Apologos), a town immediately east of Basra.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}{{sfn|Donner|1981|p=415}} According to the modern historian Isaac Hasson, Ziyad \"distinguished himself as an intelligent and open-minded secretary, who was devoted to his master and to public service ... he showed an unusual aptitude for accounting and had an excellent command of [[epistle|epistolary]] art\".{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} His skills and his assignment by Basra's military governor [[Abu Musa al-Ash'ari]] as his acting replacement while he was on a military campaign gained the attention of Caliph Umar.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} He brought Ziyad to [[Medina]], the center of the nascent Muslim state, where he further tested his skills; Ziyad's performance earned him a reward of 1,000 silver [[dirham]]s by Umar, which he used to purchase the freedom of his mother or his stepfather Ubayd.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} Soon after his return to Basra, Ziyad was made Utba's ''[[katib|k\u0101tib]]'' (scribe or secretary).{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}\n\nAfter Utba's death, Ziyad continued his service as ''k\u0101tib'' under his successors Abu Musa al-Ash'ari and [[al-Mughira ibn Shu'ba]], a member of the Thaqif who became Ziyad's mentor.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}}{{sfn|Donner|1981|p=415}}{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=119}} When al-Mughira was recalled by Umar to Medina in 638 due to charges of adultery by three accusers, including Abu Bakra Nufay and a certain Shibl ibn Ma'bad al-Bajali, both of whom were Ziyad's maternal half-brothers, Ziyad was also recalled to give his own testimony.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} His statement was partial toward al-Mughira and as a result, the charges were dismissed and the accusers were flogged.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}} During the reign of Caliph [[Uthman]] ({{reign|644|656}}), Ziyad served the caliph's appointee to Basra, [[Abdallah ibn Amir|Abd Allah ibn Amir]].{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}\n\nUthman's successor [[Ali]] ({{reign|656|661}}) appointed [[Abd Allah ibn Abbas]] governor of Basra and entrusted Ziyad with collection of the province's ''[[kharaj|khar\u0101j]]'' (land tax) and supervision of the treasury.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}}{{sfn|Madelung|1997|pp=220, 271}} According to Hasson, \"Ali's appreciation of Ziyad's talents were so great\" that he mandated Ibn Abbas heed Ziyad's counsel.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} When Ibn Abbas left Basra in 657 to accompany Ali at the [[Battle of Siffin]] against the governor of Syria, [[Muawiyah I|Mu'awiya ibn Abi Sufyan]], he left Ziyad as his acting governor.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|pp=277, 280}} During this period, he stamped out an uprising by the Banu Tamim, a major military tribal faction in the city, with critical assistance from another Basran faction, the [[Azd]].{{sfn|Madelung|1997|pp=280\u2013282}} \n\nAfter Ali returned from Siffin, his appointee to the district of [[Pars (Sasanian province)|Fars]], Sahl ibn Hunayf, was ousted by its inhabitants, after which he dispatched Ziyad.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} The people of Fars were satisfied with Ziyad's leadership and he was able to collect the district's ''khar\u0101j''.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} He remained in Fars through the remainder of Ali's rule, which ended with the caliph's assassination in 661 and the foundation of the [[Umayyad Caliphate]] under Mu'awiya.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} Afterward, he remained headquartered in a fortress in the vicinity of [[Istakhr]]. Of Ali's appointees, he held out the longest from recognizing Mu'awiya's caliphate.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=120}}{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=325}} Mu'awiya's agent, [[Busr ibn Abi Artat]], pressured Ziyad by capturing and threatening to kill three of his sons in Basra.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=120}}{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=325}} Ziyad's half-brother Abu Bakra interceded with Mu'awiya and Ziyad's sons were released.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=326}} He finally surrendered to Mu'awiya's rule in 662/63 after the intercession of al-Mughira, who Mu'awiya had appointed governor of [[Kufa]], the other main Arab garrison town of Iraq.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}}{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=121}} In the deal reached, the revenues from Fars owed to the caliphal treasury were split between Ziyad and al-Mughira, which Mu'awiya ignored.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=121}} Ziyad moved to Kufa and maintained intimate ties with al-Mughira and his family.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=122}}\n\n==Governor of Basra==\n[[File:Medieval Basra Map.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|Map of medieval Basra, showing Ziyad's divisions of the city into fifths along Arab tribal factional lines: [[Abd al-Qays]], [[Banu Tamim|Tamim]], [[Qays|Ahl al-Aliya]], [[Banu Bakr|Bakr]] and [[Azd]]]]\n\nMu'awiya formally recognized Ziyad as a son of his father [[Abu Sufyan]]. The motion was initiated when Ziyad sought clarification from the caliph about rumors of Abu Sufyan's biological paternity.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} According to Wellhausen, Mu'awiya summoned Ziyad to Damascus and recognized him as his paternal half-brother, \"so as to bind him in this way absolutely to himself and to his family\".{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=121\u2013122}} The decision was seen as scandalous by the [[Umayyad dynasty|Umayyad ruling family]].{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=121}} Mu'awiya's son [[Yazid I|Yazid]] and members from other branches of the clan, namely the extended family of [[Marwan I|Marwan ibn al-Hakam]] in Medina and Abd Allah ibn Amir, the governor of Basra, protested or threatened action against the decision.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} Ibn Amir and the Marwanids were silenced as a result of threats of force or bribes.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} Yazid's relations with Ziyad remained strained and satirical poetic verses about the event were spread by Marwan's brother Abd al-Rahman.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=121\u2013122}} Muslim scholars generally viewed the episode as one of Mu'awiya's most disreputable actions.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=332, note 55}}\n\nRealizing that Ziyad \"had both the abilities and the all-important local connections to be his right-hand man in Basra\", Mu'awiya appointed him governor of the province, according to the historian [[Hugh N. Kennedy]].{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}} He entered office in June or July 665, issuing an inaugural carrot-and-stick speech to Basra's restless population.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}} According to Hasson it was \"considered a masterpiece of eloquence\".{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} Wellhausen describes it as \"celebrated\" and the one which was called a \"[speech] without a preface\"{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=122}} because it skipped the traditional introductions praising God and blessing the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]].{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}} The speech is translated as follows: <blockquote>Ye are putting relationship before religion, ye are excusing and sheltering your criminals, and tearing down the protecting laws sanctified by Islam. Beware of prowling by night; I will kill every one who is found at night in the streets. Beware of the arbitrary summons of relationship; I will cut out the tongue of every one who raises the cry. Whoever pushes anyone into the water, whoever sets fire to another's house, whoever breaks into a house, whoever opens a grave, him will I punish for it. I make every family responsible for those belonging to it. Hatred towards myself I do not punish, but only crime. Many who are terrified at my coming will be glad of my presence, and many who are building their hopes upon it will be undeceived. I rule you with the authority of God and care for your maintenance out of the wealth of God. From you I demand obedience, and ye can demand from me justice. In whatsoever I fall short, three things there are in which I shall not be lacking: at any time I shall be ready to listen to anyone; I shall pay you your pension at the proper time, and I shall not send you to war too far away or keep you in the field overlong. Do not let yourselves be carried away by your hatred and wrath against me ; it would go ill with you if ye did. Many heads do I see tottering; let each man see to it that his own remains on his shoulders!{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=122\u2013123}}</blockquote>  \n\nA number of punitive measures along the lines of those cited in his speech were taken by Ziyad at the start of his term and largely gained for him the Basrans' respect.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=123}} He established unprecedented levels of security in the city, its Iranian dependencies to the east, i.e. Fars and [[Kerman]], and the [[Arabian Desert]] to the south. The [[Kharijites]] of Basra, many of whom were concerned more with banditry than politics, submitted to his authority.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=123\u2013124}} Under Ziyad, Basra began to take shape as a proper Islamic city.{{sfn|Pellat|1960|p=1085}} His rule saw the crude mud bricks of the city's homes replaced by more durable baked bricks and he built a [[congregational mosque]] and residential palace.{{sfn|Pellat|1960|p=1085}} In the words of the historian [[Charles Pellat]], Ziyad, \"to a certain degree, [may] be considered as the artisan of the town's prosperity\".{{sfn|Pellat|1960|p=1085}} His effective rule cemented Mu'awiya's confidence in him.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}} In the same year that Ziyad was appointed to Basra, the province of [[Eastern Arabia|Bahrayn]] (eastern Arabia) and its dependency, the [[Al-Yamamah|Yamama]] (central Arabia), were attached to Ziyad's governorship.{{sfn|Baloch|1946|p=258}}\n\n==Viceroy of Iraq and the east==\nAfter the death of al-Mughira in 670, Kufa and its dependencies were attached to Ziyad's governorship, making him the practical viceroy over Iraq and the eastern half of the Caliphate.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}}{{sfn|Hawting|2000|p=41}} He was the first to serve as the dual governor of Kufa and Basra and divided his residence between the two towns.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} In the winter he stayed in Basra and left [[Amr ibn Hurayth]] as his deputy in Kufa, while he resided in Kufa in the summer, leaving [[Samura ibn Jundab]] as his deputy in Basra.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} His strong grip in Kufa marked a shift from al-Mughira's hands-off approach.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=85}} A source of disturbance for him in Kufa was the agitation of the [[Alids]],{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} partisans of Caliph Ali, led by [[Hujr ibn Adi|Hujr ibn Adi al-Kindi]], who disapproved of Umayyad rule and led the first open calls for the caliphate to be held by Ali's progeny.{{sfn|Hawting|2000|p=41}} Though al-Mughira tolerated Hujr, Ziyad issued a number of dire warnings to cease his open dissent.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} He succeeded in turning most of Hujr's supporters among the Kufan troops against him.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}}{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=124\u2013125}} In 671, he had Hujr and thirteen of his loyalists arrested and sent to Damascus for punishment, where six, including Hujr, were executed in [[Adra, Syria|Adra]] for their refusal to renounce support for the Alids.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=337}} One of the men, Abd al-Rahman ibn Hassan al-Anazi, who was spared by Mu'awiya later insulted the caliph after refusing his invocation to condemn Ali and was sent back to Ziyad, who had him buried alive as punishment.{{sfn|Madelung|1997|p=338}}\n\nTo end the chaos in the ''[[amsar|am\u1e63ar]]'' (garrisons) of Basra and Kufa, Ziyad administratively reformed the two towns.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} From the reign of Caliph Umar, their garrisons consisted of soldiers from different tribes who were grouped together for the distribution of military stipends.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} There were seven such tribal groups in Kufa and Basra and at the head of each group was a chieftain chosen by its members who served as their representative to the government.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|pp=520\u2013521}}{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=125}} Gradually, this system had become economically inefficient and politically turbulent.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|pp=520\u2013521}} There was no control on Arab immigration into the ''am\u1e63ar'', resulting in overpopulation and in turn, increased competition over fewer resources.{{sfn|Hinds|1993|p=266}} Ziyad thus resolved to form larger divisions by unifying related clans and personally appointing their leader, which resulted in Kufa's reorganization into quarters and Basra into fifths.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} This measure enabled easier control of the two towns' inhabitants.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} Ziyad undertook further reforms in Kufa and Basra, including regularizing the timely payment of stipends, embarking on agricultural development schemes, including canal digging, and minting [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]]-style dirhams that bore his name as \"Ziyad ibn Abi Sufyan\".{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}}\n\n===Consolidation of Khurasan===\n[[File:Transoxiana 8th century.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|Map of early medieval Central Asia with [[Greater Khorasan|Khurasan]], where Ziyad settled 50,000 Arab troops and their families, and [[Balkh]] and [[Tukharistan]], where Ziyad's general led expeditions]]\n\nZiyad's authority extended to [[Greater Khorasan|Khurasan]] and [[Sistan|Sijistan]], the far eastern regions of the Caliphate which were considered dependencies of the Basra garrison.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} The Arab conquests of these areas in the 640s and 650s were akin to raids and did not firmly establish the Caliphate's power.{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=15}} Moreover, the political instability of the final years of Uthman's caliphate and the First Muslim Civil War saw local revolts which further weakened Arab authority.{{sfn|Shaban|1979|pp=26\u201327}} In 655, the Sasanian prince [[Peroz III]], backed by the army of [[Tukharistan]], attempted to reassert Persian power.{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=16}} Under previous caliphs, the vast region had been experimentally divided into separate provinces under the leadership of Arab tribal chiefs.{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=16}} Governance was largely left to local princes.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=86}} Fearing a Persian resurgence, which a fragmentary division of Khurasan could afford, Ziyad centralized the administration of the province in the small Arab garrison at Merv.{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=16}} \n\nTo relieve Basra's fiscal pressures, Ziyad recommenced the [[Muslim conquest of Transoxiana|Muslim conquests in Central Asia]].{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}}{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=86}} He organized the Arab military presence in Khurasan.{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=16}} In 667, he dispatched an army to the region under his lieutenant general [[al-Hakam ibn Amr al-Ghifari]].{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=16}}{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=86}} The latter conquered lower Tukharistan and [[Gharchistan]] and temporarily crossed the [[Oxus]] river into [[Transoxiana]], forcing Peroz to withdraw into [[Tang dynasty|Tang China]].{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=16}} Meanwhile, Ziyad's removal of dead soldiers and input of new recruits to the Iraqi army registers led to numerous tribesmen being taken off the payrolls.{{sfn|Shaban|1979|pp=31\u201332}} He dispatched 50,000 Arab soldiers and their families from Basra and Kufa to permanently settle in the Merv oasis of Khurasan.{{sfn|Shaban|1979|p=32}} The resettlement of these troops may have been a means \"to defuse possibly dangerous developments\" relating to the Arab tribal influx in the two garrison towns, according to the historian [[Gerald Hawting]].{{sfn|Hawting|2000|p=41}} As a result, the Merv oasis became home to the largest concentration of Muslims outside of the [[Fertile Crescent]].{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=86}} \n\nAl-Hakam's successor, [[Ghalib ibn Abd Allah al-Laythi]], was less successful in subduing Tukharistan and Ziyad sent another of his lieutenants, [[Rabi ibn Ziyad al-Harithi]], to stamp out the revolts in the conquered areas in 670/71.{{sfn|Shaban|1979|p=32}}{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=16}} Rabi proceeded to secure the capitulation of [[Balkh]], whose inhabitants had revolted against Arab rule, in a treaty and then destroyed the army of the [[Hephthalites|Hepthalite]] princes in [[Quhistan]].{{sfn|Shaban|1979|p=32}} In 673, Rabi's son Abd Allah extended Arab rule to the western banks of the Oxus and established tributary agreements with the fortress towns of [[Amul]] and [[Zamm]].{{sfn|Shaban|1979|p=32}} To solidify the territorial gains and supply the manpower for further conquests Ziyad intended for the Arab troops, initially concentrated in the Merv oasis, to colonize other parts of Khurasan.{{sfn|Shaban|1979|pp=32\u201334}} They were ultimately distributed between five regional garrisons under Ziyad's successors.{{sfn|Shaban|1979|p=34}}{{sfn|Gibb|1923|p=17}}\n\n==Legacy and assessment==\nZiyad died in the village of al-Thawiyya near Kufa on 23 August 673.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=519}}{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=126}} He was buried in a cemetery there that contained the graves of several Qurayshites and left an inheritance of 10,000 silver dirhams.{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=128}} During his governorship of Kufa in 675\u2013678, [[al-Dahhak ibn Qays al-Fihri]] visited Ziyad's grave and recited an elegy: <blockquote>If nobility and Islam ever immortalized a human being, <br /> They would certainly immortalize you.{{sfn|Boullata|2011|p=164}}</blockquote> A year after his death, Mu'awiya appointed Ziyad's son [[Ubayd Allah ibn Ziyad|Ubayd Allah]] as governor of Khurasan and then Basra. {{sfn|Robinson|2000|p=763}} Under Mu'awiya's son and successor, Caliph Yazid I ({{reign|680|683}}), the governorship of Kufa was also handed to Ubayd Allah.{{sfn|Robinson|2000|p=763}} Ziyad's sons [[Abd al-Rahman ibn Ziyad|Abd al-Rahman]] and [[Salm ibn Ziyad|Salm]] served successively as governors of Khurasan in 678\u2013680 and 680\u2013683/84,{{sfn|Morony|1987|pp=199, 207}}{{sfn|Bosworth|1995|p=169}} and two other sons, [[Abbad ibn Ziyad|Abbad]] and [[Yazid ibn Ziyad|Yazid]], served successively as governors of Sijistan in 673\u2013680/81 and 680/81.{{sfn|Zetterst\u00e9en|1960|p=5}}{{sfn|Bosworth|1968|p=44}} The Thaqif, which had maintained close ties with the Umayyads since the pre-Islamic era and played an integral role in the Muslim conquest of Iraq, provided the Umayyad dynasty with a series of viceroys in Iraq, including al-Mughira, Ziyad, Ubayd Allah and [[al-Hajjaj ibn Yusuf]] ({{reign|694|714}}), and the Muslim traditional sources devote more attention to them than the caliphs on whose behalf they ruled.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=113\u2013114}} Along with his mentor al-Mughira, Ziyad and his family were part of what \"some must have seen as a Thaqafi mafia\" controlling Iraq and the east, according to Kennedy.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=86}} \n\nAmong \"the most gifted governors of the Umayyad era\", Ziyad \"had a good understanding of his task as governor, and had a great influence on his successors concerning the conception of the duties of rulers\", according to Hasson.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} According to Kennedy, Ziyad's settlement of Iraqi Arab troops in Khurasan had \"extremely important consequences for Islamic history\" as the descendants of those settlers,{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=86}} who were known as ''ahl Khur\u0101s\u0101n'',{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} [[Abbasid Revolution|ultimately destroyed]] the Umayyad Caliphate as part of the [[Abbasid Caliphate|Abbasid]] army in 750.{{sfn|Kennedy|2004|p=86}} The execution of Hujr and his six partisans, all of whom had been prominent men in their own right, also led to deep-seated resentment among their Kufan kinsmen.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|pp=124\u2013125}} The incident would serve as a harbinger for future pro-Alid risings.{{sfn|Hawting|2000|p=41}} The death of Hujr represented the first political execution in Islamic history,{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}} and he and his companions are viewed as martyrs by [[Shia Muslim]]s.{{sfn|Wellhausen|1927|p=125}} Ziyad was alleged to have ordered cruel acts against some Alid partisans, including crucifixions.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=520}}\n\nInterest in Ziyad's biography emerged early on among the traditional Muslim historians, with works written about him by [[Abu Mikhnaf]] (d. 774), [[Hisham ibn al-Kalbi]] (d. 819) and Abd al-Aziz ibn Yahya al-Jaludi (d. 943).{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} He is considered a highly skilled orator among Arabs, with his inaugural speech and fragments of other speeches and sayings cited in [[Islamic literature]] and Arabic rhetoric, polemics and histories.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} He is counted alongside Mu'awiya, al-Mughira and [[Amr ibn al-As]], the conqueror and governor of Egypt, as one of the four ''duh\u0101t'' (i.e. \"shrewds\") among the Arab statesmen of his era.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} According to the medieval Syrian historian [[Ibn Asakir]] (d. 1176), Ziyad had expert knowledge of the [[Qur'an]], its tenets and [[fiqh|Islamic jurisprudence]].{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} A medieval Basran historian, Muhammad ibn Imran al-Abdi, related that Ziyad respected and enjoyed listening to the [[hadith]]s about Umar and proclaimed about them: \"This is the truth we hear! This is the [[sunnah|sunna]]!\"{{sfn|Hakim|2008|p=23}} Ziyad is credited by a number of sources for transmitting sayings by the Islamic prophet Muhammad through Umar as the original transmitter.{{sfn|Hasson|2002|p=521}} In 777 the Abbasid authorities stripped Ziyad's descendants of their status as official members of the Quraysh (the tribe to which the Umayyads and Abbasids belonged) in the ''d\u012bw\u0101n'' rolls, which entitled them to relatively high pensions, and declared them part of Thaqif, whose members were paid less.{{sfn|Tritton|1954|p=171}} At some point afterward, they were reinstated as Quraysh as a result of bribing government officials.{{sfn|Tritton|1954|p=171}}\n\n==Family==\nZiyad had numerous wives and ''[[umm walad|ummahat awlad]]'' (slave women who bore children; sing. ''umm walad'').{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=121}} He had twenty sons and twenty-three daughters, most of whom were the children of ''ummahat awlad''.{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=121}} From his first wife Mu'adha bint Sakhr of the [[Banu Uqayl]] tribe Ziyad had four sons, including Muhammad and Abd al-Rahman, who respectively married daughters of Caliph Mu'awiya I and the latter's brother [[Utba ibn Abi Sufyan|Utba]].{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=121}} His other Arab wives were Lubaba bint Awf al-Harashiyya, the daughter of a Basran noble, whose brother Zurara was a prominent Muslim jurist and one-time [[qadi]] (Islamic head judge) of Basra on Ziyad's behalf; an unnamed daughter of al-Qa'qa ibn Ma'bad ibn Zurara, a chieftain of the Darim clan of the [[Banu Tamim]] tribe who was credited for leading his tribe's first delegation to the Islamic prophet Muhammad; an unnamed daughter of Muhajir ibn Hakim ibn Taliq ibn Sufyan, a fifth-generation descendant of the Umayyad clan's progenitor [[Umayya ibn Abd Shams]]; and an unnamed woman from the [[Banu Khuza'a|Khuza'a]] tribe.{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=121}} Ziyad was also married for a time to a Sasanian Persian princess, Marjana (or Manjana), who mothered his son Ubayd Allah; she later remarried a Persian commander of Ziyad called Shiruyah al-Uswari.{{sfn|Zakeri|1995|p=116}}\n\nZiyad's daughter Ramla was a wife of the Umayyad prince [[Umayya ibn Abdallah ibn Khalid ibn Asid|Umayya]], son of Ziyad's deputy governor of Fars province or its [[Ardashir-Khwarrah|Ardashir-Khurrah]] district and later his deputy governor of Kufa, [[Abdallah ibn Khalid ibn Asid]], who led Ziyad's funeral prayers and served as Kufa's governor until 675.{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=123}} Ziyad had successively appointed Umayya as the deputy governor of [[Khuzistan]] and al-Ubulla.{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=123}} Ziyad's daughter Sakhra was married to a noble of the Qurayshite [[Makhzum]] clan, Ubaydallah ibn Abd al-Rahman ibn al-Harith, a great-grandson of [[Hisham ibn al-Mughira]].{{sfn|Fariq|1966|p=123}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite journal |last1=Baloch |first1=Nabi Bakhsh Khan |authorlink=Nabi Bakhsh Khan Baloch |title=The Probable Date of the First Arab Expeditions to India |journal=Islamic Culture |date=July 1946 |volume=20 |issue=3 |pages=250\u2013266 |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.92019/page/n324 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Bosworth |first1=C. E. |authorlink=Clifford Edmund Bosworth |title=S\u012bst\u0101n under the Arabs: From the Islamic Conquest to the Rise of the \u1e62aff\u0101rids (30\u2013250, 651\u2013864) |date=1968 |publisher=Istituto italiano per il Medio ed Estremo Oriente |location=Rome |oclc=956878036 |ref=harv}}\n*{{EI2 |article=Salm b. Ziy\u0101d b. Ab\u012bhi |last=Bosworth |first=C. E. |volume=8 |page=997}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Boullata |first1=Issa J. |title=The Unique Necklace: Al-'Iqd Al-Farid, Volume 3 |date=2011 |publisher=Garnet Publishing |location=Reading |isbn=978-1-85964-240-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dQ9KCcDUBT4C |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Donner |first1=Fred M. |authorlink=Fred M. Donner |title=The Early Islamic Conquests |date=1981 |publisher=Princeton University Press |location=Princeton |url={{Gbook|l5__AwAAQBAJ|plainurl=y}} |ref=harv}}\n*{{The Arab Conquests in Central Asia}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Fariq |first1=K. A. |title=Ziy\u0101d b. Ab\u012bh |date=1966 |publisher=Asia Publishing House |location=London |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zLtWAAAAMAAJ |oclc=581630755 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Hakim |first1=Avraham |title=\u02bfUmar b. al-\u1e2aa\u1e6d\u1e6d\u0101b: L'autorit\u00e9 religieuse et morale |journal=Arabica |date=January 2008 |volume=55 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201334 |ref=harv |publisher=Brill |language=French|jstor=25162264 |doi=10.1163/157005808X289296 }}\n*{{EI2 |article=Ziy\u0101d b. Ab\u012bhi |last=Hasson |first=I. |authorlink= |volume=11 |pages=519\u2013522}}\n*{{The First Dynasty of Islam|edition=Second}}\n*{{EI2 |article=Mu\u02bf\u0101wiya I b. Ab\u012b Sufy\u0101n |last=Hinds |first=M. |authorlink=Martin Hinds |volume=7 |pages=263\u2013268}}\n*{{The Prophet and the Age of the Caliphates|edition=Second}}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=19 |url={{Gbook||plainurl=y}}}}\n*{{ODLA|last=Lynch|first=Ryan J.|title=Ziyad b. Abi Sufyan (Ziyad b. Abihi)|url=https://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780198662778.001.0001/acref-9780198662778-e-5141?rskey=y0sSQ0&result=1|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Madelung |first1=Wilferd |authorlink=Wilferd Madelung |title=The Succession to Muhammad: A Study of the Early Caliphate |date=1997 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |isbn=0-521-56181-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2QKBUwBUWWkC |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Morony |first1=Michael |title=The Effects of the Muslim Conquest on the Persian Population of Iraq |journal=Iran |date=1976 |volume=14 |pages=41\u201359 |ref=harv|jstor=4300543 |doi=10.2307/4300543 }}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=18 |url={{Gbook|9DHhZ5Wwo_YC|plainurl=y}}}}\n*{{EI2 |article=Al-Ba\u1e63ra \u2014 Ba\u1e63ra until the Mongol conquest (656/1258) |last=Pellat |first=Ch. |authorlink=Charles Pellat |volume=1 |pages=1085\u20131086}}\n*{{EI2 |article=\u02bfUbayd All\u0101h b. Ziy\u0101d |last=Robinson |first=C. F. |authorlink=Chase F. Robinson |volume=10 |pages=763\u2013764}}\n*{{cite book |title=The 'Abb\u0101sid Revolution |first=M. A. |last=Shaban |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |year=1979 |isbn=0-521-29534-3 |url={{Gbook|1_03AAAAIAAJ|plainurl=y}} |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Tritton |first1=A. S. |title=Notes and Communications |journal=Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies |date=1954 |volume=16 |issue=1 |pages=170\u2013172 |url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/608915 |ref=harv}}\n*{{The Arab Kingdom and its Fall}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Zakeri |first1=Mohsen |title=Sasanid Soldiers in Early Muslim Society: The Origins of 'Ayy\u0101r\u0101n and Futuwwa |date=1995 |publisher=Harassowitz Verlag |location=Wiesbaden |isbn=3-447-03652-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VfYnu5F20coC&pg=PA116 |ref=harv}}\n*{{EI2 |article=\u02bfAbb\u0101d b. Ziy\u0101d |last=Zetterst\u00e9en |first=K. V. |authorlink=Karl Vilhelm Zetterst\u00e9en |volume=1 |page=5}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=Governor of [[Basra]]|before=[[Abd Allah ibn Amir]]|after=Office merged into governorship of Iraq|years=665&ndash;670}}\n{{succession box|title=Governor of Iraq|before=Office established|after=[[Samura ibn Jundab]] (Basra) <br /> [[Abdallah ibn Khalid ibn Asid]] ([[Kufa]])|years=670&ndash;673}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:622 births]]\n[[Category:673 deaths]]\n[[Category:7th-century Umayyad people]]\n[[Category:Banu Thaqif]]\n[[Category:Generals of the Umayyad Caliphate]]\n[[Category:People of the Muslim conquest of Persia]]\n[[Category:People of the Rashidun Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Umayyad governors of Basra]]\n[[Category:Umayyad governors of Iraq]]\n", "name_user": "JasonMoore", "label": "safe", "comment": "Detail", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ziyad_ibn_Abihi"}
{"title_page": "Hilda Lorimer", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = <!-- see [[MOS:CREDENTIAL]] and [[MOS:HONORIFIC]] -->\n| name               = Hilda Lorimer\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = Hilda_Lorimer.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Elizabeth Hilda Lockhart Lorimer\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|df=y|1873|5|30}} \n| birth_place        = [[Edinburgh]], Scotland\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|1954|3|1|1873|5|30}}\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| region             = \n| nationality        = Scottish\n| citizenship        = United Kingdom\n| residence          = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = \n| period             = \n| known_for          = \n| home_town          = \n| title              = \n| boards             = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation-->\n| spouse             = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            =\n| relatives          =\n| awards             = <!--notable national level awards only-->\n| website            = \n| education          = [[High School of Dundee]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Girton College, Cambridge]]\n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = \n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = \n| academic_advisors  = \n| influences         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| era                = \n| discipline         = [[Classics]]\n| sub_discipline     = {{hlist|[[Homer]]|[[Classical archaeology]]|[[Ancient Greece]]}}\n| workplaces         = [[Somerville College, Oxford]]\n| doctoral_students  = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| notable_students   = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| main_interests     = \n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Elizabeth Hilda Lockhart Lorimer''' (30 May 1873 \u2013 1 March 1954) was a British classical scholar who spent her career at [[Oxford University]]. Her best known work was in the field of [[Homeric]] archaeology and [[ancient Greece]], but she also visited and published on Turkey, Albania and the area that later became [[Yugoslavia]]. She took the position of vice-principal of [[Somerville College, Oxford|Somerville College]] during the second world war.\n\n==Family==\n[[File:The grave of Hilda Lockhart Lorimer, Warriston Cemetery.jpg|thumb|The grave of Hilda Lockhart Lorimer, Warriston Cemetery]]\nLorimer was born on 30 May 1873 in [[Edinburgh]], Scotland.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> She was the second of eight children born to Reverend Robert Lorimer and his wife. Her brother [[David Lockhart Robertson Lorimer]] was a lieutenant-colonel in the [[British Indian Army]], a [[linguist]] and a political official in the British Indian government.<ref name=UKArcF177>{{citation\n | url = http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/A2A/records.aspx?cat=059-msseur_13&cid=-1&Gsm=2008-06-18#-1\n | title = British Library, Asia, Pacific and Africa Collections; Private Papers [Mss Eur F175 \u2013 Mss Eur F199] \n | contribution = Papers of Emily Overend Lorimer, author, editor of 'Basrah Times' 1916\u201317, wife of Lt-Col David Lorimer, Indian Political Service 1903\u201327  Mss Eur F177  1902\u20131949\n | author = [[Emily Overend Lorimer]]\n | publisher = National Archives (UK)}}</ref><ref>[http://squirrel.soas.ac.uk/dserve/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqPos=0&dsqSearch=(RefNo=='PP%20MS%2066') ''Lorimer, Lieutenant-Colonel David Lockhart Robertson'', School of Oriental and African Studies (SOAS) Archive Catalogue]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Her brothers [[John Gordon Lorimer (1870-1914)|Gordon]] and Bert worked in the civil administration in the Indian Political Service.<ref name=\"Tuson2003\">{{cite book|author=Penelope Tuson|title=Playing the Game: Western Women in Arabia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sWX9GoHX46QC&pg=PA2|accessdate=23 May 2013|date=19 December 2003|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-86064-933-2|pages=2\u2013}}</ref> Another, [[William Lorimer (scholar)|William]], became Professor of Classics at [[University of St Andrews|St Andrews]]. Her sister Emilia became a notable poet, and her other sister Florence served as personal secretary to [[Aurel Stein]] at the [[British Museum]]. It was said that she could speak ancient Greek and Latin by the age of five.<ref name=soas>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soas.ac.uk/gallery/bakhtiari-kuch/eet/caricature-orientalists/index.html|title=Brunei Gallery at SOAS: Bakhtiari Kuch - Early European Travellers: Caricature Orientalists or just Men of their Time?|website=www.soas.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n\nShe never used her first name;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brown.edu/Research/Breaking_Ground/bios/Lorimer_Hilda.pdf|title=Hilda Lorimer|last=Waterhouse|first=Helen|date=|website=Breaking Ground by Brown.edu|access-date=7 December 2019}}</ref> her family called her Hiddo; and at Oxford she came to be known as Highland Hilda because of her [[Scottish people|Scottish]] background.<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite web|last1=Waterhouse|first1=Helen|title=Article Lorimer, (Elizabeth) Hilda Lockhart (1873\u20131954), classical scholar|website=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|publisher=Oxford University Press|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/48498|date=23 September 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nLorimer attended the [[High School of Dundee]] in Scotland from 1889 \u2013 1893. She was granted a scholarship to [[Girton College]] at [[Cambridge University]], where she earned a [[British_undergraduate_degree_classification#First-class_honours|first]].\n\n==Career==\nIn 1896, she became a [[Fellow (Oxbridge)|fellow]] and [[Tutorial system|tutor]] of Classics at [[Somerville College, Oxford]], which is where she spent the rest of her career. At Somerville, she had little contact with colleagues. \n\nShe was a skilled [[Latin]] linguist, but at Oxford her interests turned toward [[archaeology]]. She took a sabbatical to attend the [[British School at Athens]] in 1901 and 1902. There she began focusing on Homeric archaeology, the study of ancient civilisations known through the poems of [[Homer]].<ref>Helen Waterhouse, [http://www.brown.edu/Research/Breaking_Ground/bios/Lorimer_Hilda.pdf Breaking Ground: Women in Old World Archaeology], Brown University.</ref> In 1911, she participated in excavations at [[Phylakopi]] on [[Melos]]. [[Dorothy Lamb]], Lillian Tenant and  Lorimer were the first women to participate in an excavation conducted by the British School at Athens.<ref name=\"Hamilton\">{{cite book|last1=Hamilton|first1=Sue|last2=Whitehouse|first2=Ruth D.|last3=Wright|first3=Katherine I.|title=Archeology and Women: Ancient and Modern Issues|date=2007|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=1-59874-223-X|pages=55\u201356|edition=2nd}}</ref> The excavation, led by [[Richard MacGillivray Dawkins]], the director of the British School, was conducted from March to May 1911. The project was a supplementary excavation of a site that had been explored from 1896 to 1899.<ref name=\"Dawkins\">{{cite book|last1=Dawkins|first1=Richard|last2=Droop|first2=J.P.|title=Excavations at Phylakopi in Melos, 1911. The Annual of the British School at Athens, Volume 17|publisher=British School at Athens|location=Athens|pages=2\u20133}}</ref>\n\nIn 1917 she went to [[Salonica]] as a nursing orderly in the [[Scottish Women's Hospitals for Foreign Service|Scottish Women's Hospital]] (the Girton and Newnham Unit).<ref>{{cite web|title=Somervillians in the First World War|url=http://blogs.some.ox.ac.uk/archive/2011/01/25/somervillians-in-the-first-world-war/|website=blogs.some.ox.ac.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nLorimer took an [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|Oxford MA]] at the first opportunity, in 1920,<ref>\"Degrees conferred at Oxford\". ''[[Yorkshire Post]]'', 15 October 1920. p5.</ref> and a Cambridge MA in 1948. She returned to [[Athens]] in 1922 and became a university [[lecturer]] at Oxford from 1929 to 1937. She retired in 1939, but remained an [[honorary fellow]]. She took the position of vice-principal of Somerville College during the second world war.<ref name=soas/>\n\nShe died on 1 March 1954 and is buried with her siblings in [[Warriston Cemetery]] in north [[Edinburgh]]. The grave lies to the south-west of the now-sealed eastern entrance.\n\n==Publications==\n\nLorimer published extensively on Homeric studies throughout her career, but her seminal work came late in life with the publication of ''Homer and the Monuments''. Its publication was delayed until 1950 by the Second World War.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lorimer, Hilda}}\n[[Category:Scottish women writers]]\n[[Category:People educated at the High School of Dundee]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Scottish scientists]]\n[[Category:1873 births]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:British women scientists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Somerville College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Scottish classical scholars]]\n[[Category:Classical scholars of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Classical archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Women archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Women classical scholars]]\n[[Category:20th-century archaeologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Women's Hospitals for Foreign Service]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = <!-- see [[MOS:CREDENTIAL]] and [[MOS:HONORIFIC]] -->\n|