3 1 March 1954) was a British classical scholar who spent her career at [[Oxford University]]. Her best known work was in the field of [[Homeric]] archaeology and [[ancient Greece]], but she also visited and published on Turkey, Albania and the area that later became [[Yugoslavia]]. She took the position of vice-principal of [[Somerville College, Oxford|Somerville College]] during the second world war\n\n==Family==\n[[File:The grave of Hilda Lockhart Lorimer, Warriston Cemetery.jpg|thumb|The grave of Hilda Lockhart Lorimer, Warriston Cemetery]]\nLorimer was born on 30 May 1873 in [[Edinburgh]], Scotland.<ref name=\"ODNB\" /> She was the second of eight children born to Reverend Robert Lorimer and his wife. Her brother [[David Lockhart Robertson Lorimer]] was a lieutenant-colonel in the [[British Indian Army]], a [[linguist]] and a political official in the British Indian government.<ref name=UKArcF177>{{citation\n | url = http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/A2A/records.aspx?cat=059-msseur_13&cid=-1&Gsm=2008-06-18#-1\n | title = British Library, Asia, Pacific and Africa Collections; Private Papers [Mss Eur F175 \u2013 Mss Eur F199] \n | contribution = Papers of Emily Overend Lorimer, author, editor of 'Basrah Times' 1916\u201317, wife of Lt-Col David Lorimer, Indian Political Service 1903\u201327  Mss Eur F177  1902\u20131949\n | author = [[Emily Overend Lorimer]]\n | publisher = National Archives (UK)}}</ref><ref>[http://squirrel.soas.ac.uk/dserve/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqPos=0&dsqSearch=(RefNo=='PP%20MS%2066') ''Lorimer, Lieutenant-Colonel David Lockhart Robertson'', School of Oriental and African Studies (SOAS) Archive Catalogue]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Her brothers [[John Gordon Lorimer (1870-1914)|Gordon]] and Bert worked in the civil administration in the Indian Political Service.<ref name=\"Tuson2003\">{{cite book|author=Penelope Tuson|title=Playing the Game: Western Women in Arabia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sWX9GoHX46QC&pg=PA2|accessdate=23 May 2013|date=19 December 2003|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-86064-933-2|pages=2\u2013}}</ref> Another, [[William Lorimer (scholar)|William]], became Professor of Classics at [[University of St Andrews|St Andrews]]. Her sister Emilia became a notable poet, and her other sister Florence served as personal secretary to [[Aurel Stein]] at the [[British Museum]]. It was said that she could speak ancient Greek and Latin by the age of five.<ref name=soas>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soas.ac.uk/gallery/bakhtiari-kuch/eet/caricature-orientalists/index.html|title=Brunei Gallery at SOAS: Bakhtiari Kuch - Early European Travellers: Caricature Orientalists or just Men of their Time?|website=www.soas.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n\nShe never used her first name;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brown.edu/Research/Breaking_Ground/bios/Lorimer_Hilda.pdf|title=Hilda Lorimer|last=Waterhouse|first=Helen|date=|website=Breaking Ground by Brown.edu|access-date=7 December 2019}}</ref> her family called her Hiddo; and at Oxford she came to be known as Highland Hilda because of her [[Scottish people|Scottish]] background.<ref name=\"ODNB\">{{cite web|last1=Waterhouse|first1=Helen|title=Article Lorimer, (Elizabeth) Hilda Lockhart (1873\u20131954), classical scholar|website=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|publisher=Oxford University Press|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/48498|date=23 September 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nLorimer attended the [[High School of Dundee]] in Scotland from 1889 \u2013 1893. She was granted a scholarship to [[Girton College]] at [[Cambridge University]], where she earned a [[British_undergraduate_degree_classification#First-class_honours|first]].\n\n==Career==\nIn 1896, she became a [[Fellow (Oxbridge)|fellow]] and [[Tutorial system|tutor]] of Classics at [[Somerville College, Oxford]], which is where she spent the rest of her career. At Somerville, she had little contact with colleagues. \n\nShe was a skilled [[Latin]] linguist, but at Oxford her interests turned toward [[archaeology]]. She took a sabbatical to attend the [[British School at Athens]] in 1901 and 1902. There she began focusing on Homeric archaeology, the study of ancient civilisations known through the poems of [[Homer]].<ref>Helen Waterhouse, [http://www.brown.edu/Research/Breaking_Ground/bios/Lorimer_Hilda.pdf Breaking Ground: Women in Old World Archaeology], Brown University.</ref> In 1911, she participated in excavations at [[Phylakopi]] on [[Melos]]. [[Dorothy Lamb]], Lillian Tenant and  Lorimer were the first women to participate in an excavation conducted by the British School at Athens.<ref name=\"Hamilton\">{{cite book|last1=Hamilton|first1=Sue|last2=Whitehouse|first2=Ruth D.|last3=Wright|first3=Katherine I.|title=Archeology and Women: Ancient and Modern Issues|date=2007|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=1-59874-223-X|pages=55\u201356|edition=2nd}}</ref> The excavation, led by [[Richard MacGillivray Dawkins]], the director of the British School, was conducted from March to May 1911. The project was a supplementary excavation of a site that had been explored from 1896 to 1899.<ref name=\"Dawkins\">{{cite book|last1=Dawkins|first1=Richard|last2=Droop|first2=J.P.|title=Excavations at Phylakopi in Melos, 1911. The Annual of the British School at Athens, Volume 17|publisher=British School at Athens|location=Athens|pages=2\u20133}}</ref>\n\nIn 1917 she went to [[Salonica]] as a nursing orderly in the [[Scottish Women's Hospitals for Foreign Service|Scottish Women's Hospital]] (the Girton and Newnham Unit).<ref>{{cite web|title=Somervillians in the First World War|url=http://blogs.some.ox.ac.uk/archive/2011/01/25/somervillians-in-the-first-world-war/|website=blogs.some.ox.ac.uk|accessdate=5 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nLorimer took an [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|Oxford MA]] at the first opportunity, in 1920,<ref>\"Degrees conferred at Oxford\". ''[[Yorkshire Post]]'', 15 October 1920. p5.</ref> and a Cambridge MA in 1948. She returned to [[Athens]] in 1922 and became a university [[lecturer]] at Oxford from 1929 to 1937. She retired in 1939, but remained an [[honorary fellow]]. She took the position of vice-principal of Somerville College during the second world war.<ref name=soas/>\n\nShe died on 1 March 1954 and is buried with her siblings in [[Warriston Cemetery]] in north [[Edinburgh]]. The grave lies to the south-west of the now-sealed eastern entrance.\n\n==Publications==\n\nLorimer published extensively on Homeric studies throughout her career, but her seminal work came late in life with the publication of ''Homer and the Monuments''. Its publication was delayed until 1950 by the Second World War.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lorimer, Hilda}}\n[[Category:Scottish women writers]]\n[[Category:People educated at the High School of Dundee]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Scottish scientists]]\n[[Category:1873 births]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:British women scientists]]\n[[Category:First women admitted to degrees at Oxford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Somerville College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Scottish classical scholars]]\n[[Category:Classical scholars of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Classical archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Women archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Women classical scholars]]\n[[Category:20th-century archaeologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Women's Hospitals for Foreign Service]]\n", "name_user": "Aivin G.", "label": "safe", "comment": "period", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilda_Lorimer"}
